{"title_page": "Butetown branch line", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name                            = Butetown branch line\n| image                           = ButeTownBranchLine-02.jpg\n| type                            = Heavy Rail\n| system                          = [[National Rail]]\n| locale                          = [[Cardiff]]\n| start                           = {{stnlnk|Cardiff Bay}}\n| end                             = {{stnlnk|Cardiff Queen Street}}\n| stations                        = 2\n| open                            = 1840\n| owner                           = [[Network Rail]]\n| operator                        = [[Transport for Wales Rail|Transport for Wales]]\n| character                       =\n| stock                           = {{brc|150}}<br>{{brc|153}}\n| linelength                      = {{convert|1|mi|6|chain|km|lk=in}}\n| tracks                          = [[Single track (rail)|Single track]] throughout\n| gauge                           = {{track gauge|uksg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge                       =\n| speed                           =\n}}\n\nThe '''Butetown branch line''', also known as the '''Cardiff Bay Line''', is a {{convert|1|mi|6|chain|km|lk=in|adj=on}} [[Commuter rail in the United Kingdom|commuter]] [[railway line]] in [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]] from [[Cardiff Bay]] and [[Cardiff Queen Street railway station|Cardiff Queen Street]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Yonge |first1=John |last2=Padgett |first2=David |editor-last=Bridge |editor-first=Mike |title=Railway Track Diagrams 3: Western |edition=5th |date=August 2010 |origyear=1989 |publisher=Trackmaps |location=Bradford on Avon |isbn=978-0-9549866-6-7 |at=maps 22 & 28B |ref=harv }}</ref> The service pattern used to comprise a mixture of shuttle services along the branch and through trains along the [[Rhymney Line]] to [[Caerphilly]], or the [[Coryton Line]] to [[Coryton, Cardiff|Coryton]], but since December 2005 is a shuttle service from [[Cardiff Queen Street railway station|Queen Street station]].\n\n==History==\n{{stack|[[File:BubbleatCQB.JPG|thumb|121032 at Cardiff Bay station]]}}\nOriginally a portion of the [[Taff Vale Railway|Taff Vale Railway's]] main line to Cardiff's [[Bute Docks]], in 1922, it was absorbed, along with the neighbouring [[Rhymney Railway]], into the enlarged [[Great Western Railway]]. With the decline of coal traffic and the closure of the Bute Docks, it now sees only passenger services, and is regarded as a branch from the line through to {{rws|Cardiff Central}}.\n\nAt privatisation in 1995, services were operated by the Cardiff Railway Company, which traded as [[Valley Lines (train operating company)|Valley Lines]].  This was subsumed by the new [[Wales & Borders]] franchise in 2001, which was subsequently awarded to [[Arriva UK Trains]] in December 2003 and operated as [[Arriva Trains Wales]]. In October 2018, [[Transport for Wales Rail|Transport for Wales]] took over the franchise from Arriva Trains Wales.\n\nThe December 2005 timetable introduced a further increase in services to 4 trains per hour 18 hours a day, and even a Sunday service for the first time (further improved in June 2006 to offer the same 4 trains per hour service from 11am to 4pm). In December 2005, Arriva employed a single car [[British Rail Class 153|Class 153]] to \"shuttle\" along the Butetown Line, upgrading from the 2 car [[British Rail Class 143|Class 143]] 'Pacers' used for the service. Since then, the service frequency has been increased even more \u2013 there are now 5 trains per hour on the line every day of the week, which equates to one train every 12 minutes.\n\nIn July 2006 the service was due to be provided by a 1950s {{BRC|121}} \"Bubble car\" DMU. The unit finally entered service on 17 August 2006, only to be withdrawn for repairs two days later. The unit then re-entered service on 14 September 2006.\n\n{{Butetown Branch Line}}\n\n==Passenger volume==\nBelow is the passenger volume from the year beginning April 2002 to the year beginning April 2015. Comparing the two years, Cardiff Queen Street's usage has increased by 44% whilst Cardiff Bay has increased 569%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rail-reg.gov.uk/server/show/nav.1529|publisher=[[Office of Rail Regulation]]|accessdate=10 May 2012|title=Station usage}}</ref>\n\n{{GBsta-u|\n{{GBsta-u A|stn=Cardiff Queen Street|u1=1,841,260|u2=2,072,551|u3=2,126,479|u4=2,231,784|u5=2,486,005|u6=2,559,748|u7=2,437,638|u8=2,411,438|u9=2,488,920|u10=2,495,238|u11=2,462,700|u12=2,523,314|u13=2,643,568}}\n{{GBsta-u A|stn=Cardiff Bay|u1=177,911|u2=245,910|u3=274,133|u4=404,049|u5=518,572|u6=594,520|u7=685,608|u8=753,148|u9=793,382|u10=869,126|u11=1,019,348|u12=1,143,746|u13=1,190,780}}\n}}\n\n==Modernisation==\nOn 16 July 2012, plans to electrify the line were announced by the government, as part of a \u00a39.4bn package of investment of the railways in England and Wales.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18851907 BBC News \u2013 \u00a39bn railway investment announced by coalition<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nThe announcement was made as an extension of the electrification of the [[South Wales Main Line]] from Cardiff to Swansea and the electrification of the south Wales [[Valleys & Cardiff Local Routes|Valley Lines]] at a total cost of \u00a3350 million. It was proposed to start between 2014 and 2019.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-18852955 BBC News \u2013 Rail electrification to Swansea and south Wales valleys welcomed<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn June 2018 it was announced by the new operator [[Transport for Wales Rail]] that the line was to be re-integrated into Valley Lines services, with 6 trains per hour to operate from Merthyr Tydfil, Aberdare and Treherbert.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tfw.gov.wales/whats-happening-south-east-wales|title=What's Happening in South East Wales {{!}} Transport for Wales|website=tfw.gov.wales|language=en|access-date=25 October 2018}}</ref> New stations will be constructed at [[Loudoun Square railway station|Loudoun Square]] and [[Cardiff Bay (The Flourish) railway station|on a short extension from the current station]] closer to Cardiff Bay, opening in December 2023. The current Cardiff Bay station will close at the same time. [[Stadler Citylink]] tram-trains will replace the [[British Rail Class 153|Class 153s]]. These will switch to battery power on the branch, negating the need for electrification.<ref>https://www.walesonline.co.uk/business/business-news/huge-investment-running-billions-transform-14738004</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of railway stations in Cardiff]]\n* [[Cardiff Riverside Branch]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Butetown Branch Line}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Railway lines in Wales}}\n{{Transport in Cardiff}}\n{{South Wales Metro}}\n\n[[Category:Butetown]]\n[[Category:Railway lines in Wales]]\n[[Category:Transport in Cardiff]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name                            = Butetown branch line\n| image                           = ButeTownBranchLine-02.jpg\n| type                            = Heavy Rail\n| system                          = [[National Rail]]\n| locale                          = [[Cardiff]]\n| start                           = {{stnlnk|Cardiff Bay}}\n| end                             = {{stnlnk|Cardiff Queen Street}}\n| stations                        = 2\n| open                            = 1840\n| owner                           = [[Network Rail]]\n| operator                        = [[Transport for Wales Rail|Transport for Wales]]\n| character                       = \n| stock                           = {{brc|150}}<br>{{brc|153}}\n| linelength                      = {{convert|1|mi|6|chain|km|lk=in}}\n| tracks                          = [[Single track (rail)|Single track]] throughout\n| gauge                           = {{track gauge|uksg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge                       = \n| speed                           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Butetown branch line''', also known as the '''Cardiff Bay Line''', is a {{convert|1|mi|6|chain|km|lk=in|adj=on}} [[Commuter rail in the United Kingdom|commuter]] [[railway line]] in [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]] from [[Cardiff Bay]] and [[Cardiff Queen Street railway station|Cardiff Queen Street]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Yonge |first1=John |last2=Padgett |first2=David |editor-last=Bridge |editor-first=Mike |title=Railway Track Diagrams 3: Western |edition=5th |date=August 2010 |origyear=1989 |publisher=Trackmaps |location=Bradford on Avon |isbn=978-0-9549866-6-7 |at=maps 22 & 28B |ref=harv }}</ref> The service pattern used to comprise a mixture of shuttle services along the branch and through trains along the [[Rhymney Line]] to [[Caerphilly]], or the [[Coryton Line]] to [[Coryton, Cardiff|Coryton]], but since December 2005 is a shuttle service from [[Cardiff Queen Street railway station|Queen Street station]].\n\n==History==\n{{stack|[[File:BubbleatCQB.JPG|thumb|121032 at Cardiff Bay station]]}}\nOriginally a portion of the [[Taff Vale Railway|Taff Vale Railway's]] main line to Cardiff's [[Bute Docks]], in 1922, it was absorbed, along with the neighbouring [[Rhymney Railway]], into the enlarged [[Great Western Railway]]. With the decline of coal traffic and the closure of the Bute Docks, it now sees only passenger services, and is regarded as a branch from the line through to {{rws|Cardiff Central}}.\n\nAt privatisation in 1995, services were operated by the Cardiff Railway Company, which traded as [[Valley Lines (train operating company)|Valley Lines]].  This was subsumed by the new [[Wales & Borders]] franchise in 2001, which was subsequently awarded to [[Arriva UK Trains]] in December 2003 and operated as [[Arriva Trains Wales]]. In October 2018, [[Transport for Wales Rail|Transport for Wales]] took over the franchise from Arriva Trains Wales.\n\nThe December 2005 timetable introduced a further increase in services to 4 trains per hour 18 hours a day, and even a Sunday service for the first time (further improved in June 2006 to offer the same 4 trains per hour service from 11am to 4pm). In December 2005, Arriva employed a single car [[British Rail Class 153|Class 153]] to \"shuttle\" along the Butetown Line, upgrading from the 2 car [[British Rail Class 143|Class 143]] 'Pacers' used for the service. Since then, the service frequency has been increased even more \u2013 there are now 5 trains per hour on the line every day of the week, which equates to one train every 12 minutes.\n\nIn July 2006 the service was due to be provided by a 1950s {{BRC|121}} \"Bubble car\" DMU. The unit finally entered service on 17 August 2006, only to be withdrawn for repairs two days later. The unit then re-entered service on 14 September 2006.\n\n{{Butetown Branch Line}}\n\n==Passenger volume==\nBelow is the passenger volume from the year beginning April 2002 to the year beginning April 2015. Comparing the two years, Cardiff Queen Street's usage has increased by 44% whilst Cardiff Bay has increased 569%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rail-reg.gov.uk/server/show/nav.1529|publisher=[[Office of Rail Regulation]]|accessdate=10 May 2012|title=Station usage}}</ref>\n\n{{GBsta-u|\n{{GBsta-u A|stn=Cardiff Queen Street|u1=1,841,260|u2=2,072,551|u3=2,126,479|u4=2,231,784|u5=2,486,005|u6=2,559,748|u7=2,437,638|u8=2,411,438|u9=2,488,920|u10=2,495,238|u11=2,462,700|u12=2,523,314|u13=2,643,568}}\n{{GBsta-u A|stn=Cardiff Bay|u1=177,911|u2=245,910|u3=274,133|u4=404,049|u5=518,572|u6=594,520|u7=685,608|u8=753,148|u9=793,382|u10=869,126|u11=1,019,348|u12=1,143,746|u13=1,190,780}}\n}}\n\n==Modernisation==\nOn 16 July 2012, plans to electrify the line were announced by the government, as part of a \u00a39.4bn package of investment of the railways in England and Wales.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18851907 BBC News \u2013 \u00a39bn railway investment announced by coalition<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nThe announcement was made as an extension of the electrification of the [[South Wales Main Line]] from Cardiff to Swansea and the electrification of the south Wales [[Valleys & Cardiff Local Routes|Valley Lines]] at a total cost of \u00a3350 million. It was proposed to start between 2014 and 2019.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-18852955 BBC News \u2013 Rail electrification to Swansea and south Wales valleys welcomed<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn June 2018 it was announced by the new operator [[Transport for Wales Rail]] that the line was to be re-integrated into Valley Lines services, with 6 trains per hour to operate from Merthyr Tydfil, Aberdare and Treherbert.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tfw.gov.wales/whats-happening-south-east-wales|title=What's Happening in South East Wales {{!}} Transport for Wales|website=tfw.gov.wales|language=en|access-date=25 October 2018}}</ref> New stations will be constructed at [[Loudoun Square railway station|Loudoun Square]] and [[Cardiff Bay (The Flourish) railway station|on a short extension from the current station]] closer to Cardiff Bay, opening in December 2023. The current Cardiff Bay station will close at the same time. [[Stadler Citylink]] tram-trains will replace the [[British Rail Class 153|Class 153s]]. These will switch to battery power on the branch, negating the need for electrification.<ref>https://www.walesonline.co.uk/business/business-news/huge-investment-running-billions-transform-14738004</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of railway stations in Cardiff]]\n*[[Cardiff Riverside Branch]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Butetown Branch Line}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Railway lines in Wales}}\n{{Transport in Cardiff}}\n{{South Wales Metro}}\n\n[[Category:Butetown]]\n[[Category:Railway lines in Wales]]\n[[Category:Transport in Cardiff]]\n", "name_user": "Davey2010", "label