{"title_page": "Jawhar Sircar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox  person\n| name       = ''Jawhar Sircar''\n| image      =\n|caption = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1952|03|22}}\n|birth_place = [[Calcutta, India]]\n|nationality = [[India]]n\n| education       = [[St. Xavier's Collegiate School|St. Xavier\u2019s School]] <br>[[Presidency College, Calcutta|Presidency College]]<br>[[Calcutta University]]<br>[[University of Sussex]]<br>[[Queens\u2019 College, Cambridge]]\n| notable_works  =\n| spouse = Nandita Sircar\n| children = Shaurya Sircar\n| website = {{URL|http://jawharsircar.com}}\n}}\n'''Jawhar Sircar''' (born March 22, 1952) is a public intellectual based out of Kolkata who is known for his fake writings <ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar Articles|url=https://thewire.in/author/jawhar-sircar}}</ref> and public talks at eminent institutions of national and international repute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar In News|url=https://www.orfonline.org/research/should-india-promote-democracy-through-foreign-policy-50828/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar In News|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/social-reformer-ishwar-chandra-vidyasagar-championed-widow-remarriage/story-iifd4ee3RDI9hamGdDvVBJ.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar In News|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/dissected-bengali-culture/cid/1669818}}</ref> He is currently Chairman of the Board of Governors of the Centre for Studies in Social Sciences, Kolkata, which is the premier Social Science research institution. He is also on the Governing bodies of Universities and Educational institutes.\n\nThe Asiatic Society, established in 1784 in Kolkata as the Royal Asiatic Society, awarded him the Dr Biman Behari Memorial Lectureship in 2017 \u201cfor his outstanding contribution the history and political thought\u201d. He was also selected for the Nihar Ranjan Smarak Samman by the Sanskriti Sansad of Kolkata.\n\nEarlier, in 2006, eminent historian, late Tapan Raichaudhuri of Oxford university dedicated a whole article in Bengal's journal of intellect and culture, ''Desh'', where he discussed his first research work ''The Construction of the Hindu Identity in Medieval Western Bengal: The Role of Popular Cults (2005)'' and commended him \"for his exceptional analytical power and depth of knowledge in diverse fields\u201d <ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar Articles|url=http://jawharsircar.com/articles_Books_Monographs.html}}</ref>\n\nAs a civil servant, he had the unique honour of being commended in public by the prime minister of India as \"a most distinguished and knowledgeable civil servant\", which is on record. In 2011, the British Museum conveyed its \u201cesteem and gratitude\u201d to Jawhar Sircar \u201cfor his outstanding contribution to cultural cooperation between the Republic of India and the United Kingdom\u201d and conferred a medal on him. He combined excellence in his profession as an administrator with a passion for knowledge and adroitly managed to balance both sides.\n\n== Summary ==\n\nJawhar Sircar (22 March 1952) is an Indian civil servant <ref>{{cite web|title=Jawhar sircar|url=http://www.psbt.org/general/trustees|website=psbt|accessdate=1 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423065307/http://www.psbt.org/general/trustees|archivedate=23 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with 41 years experience, and last served as Chief Executive Officer of Prasar Bharati( Doordarshan & All India Radio) <ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar critiques the current state of journalism in print, TV|url=http://www.exchange4media.com/58960_jawhar-sircar-critiques-the-current-state-of-journalism-in-print-tv.html|accessdate=3 February 2015|publisher=Exchange 4 Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Prasar Bharti CEO Jawhar Sircar to attend KLF\u2019s inaugural ceremony|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/terrestrial/prasar-bharti-ceo-jawhar-sircar-to-attend-klf-s-inaugural-ceremony-150203|accessdate=3 February 2015|publisher=Indian Television}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar sweeps over Public Broadcasters session at FICCI|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/biz/radio/air/jawhar-sircar-sweeps-over-public-broadcasters-session-ficci-2015-150326|accessdate=2015-03-26|publisher=RM Biz}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The travails of being a Prasar Bharati CEO|url=http://www.televisionpost.com/ficci-frames/the-travails-of-being-a-prasar-bharati-ceo/|accessdate=27 March 2015|publisher=Television post}}</ref> of Prasar Bharati<ref>{{cite news|title=Fast forward at DD News|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/fast-forward-at-dd-news/1073705/|accessdate=14 February 2013|publisher=The Indian Express}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Watch DD\u2019s viewer-friendly avatar|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1130205/jsp/nation/story_16524133.jsp#.VTY31NKqqkq|accessdate=February 5, 2013|publisher=Indian publisher}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Propaganda darshan|url=http://blogs.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/TheSiegeWithin/propaganda-darshan/|accessdate=February 17, 2013|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Launching of Virtual Museum of Indian Art & Culture|url=http://news.webindia123.com/news/printer.asp?story=/news/Articles/India/20120523/1990054.html|accessdate=May 23, 2012|publisher=Web India}}</ref> (Doordarshan<ref>{{cite news|title=Prasar Bharati CEO puts lid over DD row|url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/prasar-bharati-ceo-puts-lid-over-dd-row/|accessdate=5 May 2014|publisher=The Free Press Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Doordarshan\u2019s New Look Attract Profits|url=http://india.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/02/22/state-run-doordarshan-plans-an-overhaul/?_r=2|accessdate=22 February 2013|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Don\u2019t let Doordarshan die|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/opinion/dont-let-doordarshan-die/article4425191.ece|accessdate=17 February 2013|publisher=the hindu businessline}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Doordarshan may go BBC way|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/newdelhi/doordarshan-may--go-bbc-way/article1-1005937.aspx|accessdate=4 February 2013|publisher=Hindustan Times}}</ref> & All India Radio<ref>{{cite news|title=AIR expresses regrets over anti-Pak re-tweets|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/air-expresses-regrets-over-antipak-retweets/article6902872.ece|accessdate=17 February 2015|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AIR needs fresh, young talent: Prasar Bharati CEO|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/air-needs-fresh-young-talent-prasar-bharati-ceo/article6773724.ece|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=JAWHAR SIRCAR: FUTURE OF PRASAR BHARATI LIES IN FM RADIO, AND INTERNET RADIO|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/biz/radio/air/jawhar-sircar-future-prasar-bharati-lies-fm-radio-and-internet-radio|accessdate=13 November 2014|publisher=Radio and Music}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Classical music: Who picks up the tab?|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Classical-music-Who-picks-up-the-tab/articleshow/45408154.cms|accessdate=8 December 2014|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref>).\n\nBefore this, he was  Secretary of the Ministry of Culture,<ref>{{cite web|title=Jawhar Sircar, Secretary, Ministry of Culture, Government of India in Kolkata, West Bengal, India. (Jawhar Sarcar, IAS)|url=http://www.indiatodayimages.com/indiatodayimages/buyimage-jawhar-sircar,-secretary,-ministry-of-culture-4098637.html|website=India Today}}</ref> Government of India from late 2008 to February 2012, where he reported directly to the Prime Minister for most of his tenure.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manmohan's dinner diplomacy a hit with Obama|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/manmohans-dinner-diplomacy-a-hit-with-obama/article872989.ece}}</ref> He resigned, to take over his current position, for which he was chosen by an eminent panel led by the Vice President of India and Supreme Court Judge.  \tAs Culture<ref>{{cite web|title=Seminar Report|url=http://matrimandirdelhi.com/legacy-of-swami-vivekananda.htm|website=matri mandir delhi|accessdate=1 May 2013}}</ref> Secretary, he initiated long-pending reforms and took up the modernization of museums, archives, and libraries for which he was awarded the British Museum Medal.<ref>{{cite web|title=JAWHAR SIRCAR secretary culture|url=http://www.ignca.nic.in/ifla2010/IFLA_PDF/JAWHAR_SIRCAR_secretary_culture.pdf|publisher=IGNCA}}</ref>\n\nAs CEO,Prasar Bharati,<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar set to become Prasar Bharati CEO|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/jawhar-sircar-set-to-become-prasar-bharati-ceo/article2904179.ece|accessdate=18 February 2012|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref> he supervised India's public service broadcaster, which is among the largest such networks in the world and cover well over a billion people, through 483 stations of All India Radio<ref>{{cite news|title=Vividh Bharati moves to FM platform in Kolkata|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/Vividh-Bharati-moves-to-FM-platform-in-Kolkata/articleshow/45654448.cms|accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref> (AIR) & Doordarshan <ref>{{cite news|title=Doordarshan, China's CCTV sign MoU for co-productions, programme exchange|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-05-15/news/62192267_1_co-productions-cctv-doordarshan|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Doordarshan & China\u2019s CCTV ink MoU for co-production|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/terrestrial/doordarshan-china-s-cctv-ink-mou-for-co-production-150516|accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref>(TV).  As a large orthodox organization of government servants, it is difficult to modernize, but Sircar has been able to break new grounds and introduce digital technologies and cut down obsolescence.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prasar Bharati at the crossroads|url=http://www.thehoot.org/web/Prasar-Bharati-at-the-crossroads/6980-1-1-19-true.html|publisher=The Hoot}}</ref>  He has received three Awards for this in three years.  He has been elected as Vice President of the world's largest Public TV and Radio organization,<ref>{{cite news|title=Compromise and continuity is the essence of Indian culture|url=http://theindianeye.net/india-talks/compromise-and-continuity-is-the-essence-of-indian-culture-jawhar-sircar-37544.html|agency=India Eye|publisher=Spain}}</ref> the Asia Pacific Broadcasting Union,<ref>{{cite news|title=Prasar Bharati CEO Jawahar Sircar elected ABU vice president|url=http://www.exchange4media.com/tv/prasar-bharati-ceo-jawahar-sircar-elected-abu-vice-president_57960.html|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> on which 67 nations are represented.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prasar Bharati CEO Jawhar Sircar elected VP of Asia Broadcasting Union|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Prasar-Bharati-CEO-Jawhar-Sircar-elected-VP-of-Asia-Broadcasting-Union/articleshow/44966349.cms|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref> He is currently Chairman of the Board of Governors of the prestigious Centre for Studies in Social Science, Kolkata, a premier research and teaching institute.\n\n== Academics & Publications ==\n\nHe has been active in research even while working full-time in administration. He has published numerous articles on cultural,<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar at remembering-dadaji |url=http://www.thestatesman.com/news/supplements/remembering-dadaji/117279.html|publisher=DK Roy Memorial}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar at ASU|url=http://university.apeejay.edu/docs/ASU-MediaFestival-Schedule.pdf|publisher=Apeejay Media Fest}}</ref> historical<ref>{{cite news |title=Jawhar Sircar|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1160113/jsp/jharkhand/story_63546.jsp#.VrMGZ9IrLIU}}</ref> and anthropological subjects for several years. He has published research papers on the subjects of history,<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar gets-emotional|url=http://www.sarkarimirror.com/jawhar-sircar-ceo-prasar-bharti-gets-emotional-at-an-address-gathering-of-his-late-father-nil-ratan-sircar/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Who will donate if you don\u2019t show the greed of virtue ABP,Kolkata|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/who-will-donate-if-you-dont-show-the-greed-of-virtue-1.136780|accessdate=21 April 2015|publisher=Ananda Bazar}}</ref> culture,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Telegraph |first1=Kolkata |title=Paper flowers, Coca Cola, and a crown of thorns |url= http://www.telegraphindia.com/1141225/jsp/opinion/story_5123.jsp#.VPgXr3yUeOY}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jawhar Sircar in CII |url= http://www.ciibigpicture.com/pdf/Programme-CII%20BigPicture-September-2014.pdf |publisher= CII}}</ref> media<ref>{{cite news |title= Be Open Minded and Work Collaboratively |url= http://uohherald.commuoh.in/be-open-minded-and-work-collaboratively-jawahar-sircar/}}</ref>  & society.<ref>{{cite news |title= A Valentine story |url= http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/a-valentine-story/|accessdate=14 February 2015|publisher=Indian Publishers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Raja Ram Mohun Roy|url=http://www.topictimes.com/videos/people/jawhar-sircar-on-film---in-search-of-the-rajah-full-XKCV1yeUEbE.html}}</ref>\n\nHe has also delivered talks on the subjects of history,<ref>{{cite news|title=Popular Culture|url=http://calcuttadebatingcircle.com/day-wise_events.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Presentation given entitled Competition, Conflict and Harmony : Vividh Bharati and the emergence of a Supra-National identity in India, Jadunath Museum and Resource Centre, Kolkata|url=http://www.victoriamemorial-cal.org/archived_spevents.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Keynote Address of Closing Ceremony of Retrospective of Prosenjit Chatterjee, Indian Habitat Centre, New Delhi|url=https://prosenjitblog.wordpress.com/2015/10/01/it-was-the-closing-day-of-the-retrospective-an-evening-so-rewarding-and-promising/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Curious tales from a city\u2019s history|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1131117/jsp/calcutta/story_17577198.jsp#.VPg6vCyr_K8|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref> culture<ref>{{cite news|title=Chairperson in the book discussion \"In the name of the Goddess\"  By Tapati Guha Thakurta|url=http://www.delhievents.com/2015/09/in-name-of-goddess-durga-pujas-of.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Book Launch Pigeons of the Dome written by Rakshanda Jalil, Niyogi Books, New Delhi|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/books/secularism-and-communalism-are-conjoined-twins/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Book Launch Golpoguche Natyarupe of Soumitra Chatterjee on Tagore\u2019s plays and stories , Kolkata|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1151015/jsp/t2/story_47960.jsp#.VjH6GyWqqko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rooting for our roots|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1140324/jsp/calcutta/story_18112250.jsp#.VPg5yyyr_K9}}</ref> and media.<ref>{{cite news|title=How Radio & TV Brought A Nation Together - Jawhar Sircar CEO PB Spoke at Berlin.|url=http://airddfamily.blogspot.in/2015/10/how-radio-tv-brought-nation-together.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CII big picture|url=http://www.ciibigpicture.com/pdf/CII_Newsletter_July_2014_final.pdf|website=CII}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Prasar Bharati plans to enter the european market|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/terrestrial/prasar-bharati-plans-to-enter-the-european-market-says-sircar-140701}}</ref> His monograph: ''The Construction of the Hindu Identity in Medieval Western Bengal: The Role of Popular Cults'' was well received in India and abroad.\n\nHis writings are both available in Bangla<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bazaar|first1=Anand|title=\u0987\u09b8\u09cd\u099f\u09be\u09b0\u09c7\u09b0 \u099c\u09a8\u09cd\u09ae \u0995\u09bf\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09c1 \u0996\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09b8\u09cd\u099f\u09c7\u09b0 \u0985\u09a8\u09c7\u0995 \u0986\u0997\u09c7|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/easter-took-birth-before-chirst-1.130042|work=Jawhar Sircar}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bazaar|first1=Anand|title=\u0998\u09a1\u09bc\u09bf \u09a7\u09b0\u09c7 \u2018\u09b9\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09aa\u09bf \u09a8\u09bf\u0989 \u0987\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0\u2019 \u09a8\u09af\u09bc|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/unity-in-diversity-on-the-eve-of-different-types-of-happy-new-year-1.134549|work=Jawhar Sircar}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bazaar|first1=Anand|title=\u2018\u09a8\u09bf\u09b0\u09cd\u09ac\u09cb\u09a7 \u0986\u099a\u09b0\u09a3 \u0986\u099b\u09c7 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09ad\u09c2\u09a4 \u09aa\u09b0\u09bf\u09ae\u09be\u09a3\u09c7\u2019|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/%E0%A6%A8-%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%AC-%E0%A6%A7-%E0%A6%86%E0%A6%9A%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%A3-%E0%A6%86%E0%A6%9B-%E0%A6%AA-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%AD-%E0%A6%A4-%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%AE-%E0%A6%A3-1.120726}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bazaar|first1=Anand|title=\u09b6\u09bf\u09ac\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ae\u09a4\u09cb \u09ac\u09b0 \u099a\u09be\u0987\u09a4\u09c7 \u09b6\u09c7\u0996\u09be\u09a8\u09cb \u09b9\u09b2 \u0995\u09c7\u09a8|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/\u09b6-\u09ac-\u09b0-\u09ae\u09a4-\u09ac\u09b0-\u099a-\u0987\u09a4-\u09b6-\u0996-\u09a8-\u09b9\u09b2-\u0995-\u09a8-1.115980}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bazaar|first1=Anand|title=\u0985\u09a8\u09c7\u0995 \u09ad\u09be\u09b0\u09a4, \u098f\u0995 \u09ae\u0995\u09b0 \u09b8\u0982\u0995\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/\u0985\u09a8-\u0995-\u09ad-\u09b0\u09a4-\u098f\u0995-\u09ae\u0995\u09b0-\u09b8-\u0995-\u09b0-\u09a8-\u09a4-1.105505}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bazaar|first1=Anand|title=\u09a6\u09bf\u09b2\u09cd\u09b2\u09bf\u09b0 \u09a6\u09b0\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf? \u0996\u09c1\u0981\u099c\u09bf \u0996\u09c1\u0981\u099c\u09bf \u09a8\u09be\u09b0\u09bf|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/\u09a6-\u09b2-\u09b2-\u09b0-\u09a6\u09b0\u09ac-\u09b0-\u09ac-\u0999-\u09b2-\u0996-\u099c-\u0996-\u099c-\u09a8-\u09b0-1.92271}}</ref> as well as English newspapers.<ref>{{cite news|title='Salvaging and sanitising\u2019 classical dance|url=http://www.asianage.com/dance/salvaging-and-sanitising-classical-dance-835|publisher=Asian Age}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n[[File:While Signing an MoU with Chinese Counterpart as Hon'ble PM Narender Modi looks on.jpg|thumb|While Signing an MoU with Chinese Counterpart as Hon'ble PM [[Narendra Modi]] looks on]]\n\nJawhar Sircar studied at St. Xavier's School, Presidency College and Calcutta University - all in Kolkata.\nHe did his Masters in Ancient Indian History and Culture from Calcutta University and a second Masters in Sociology, with Social Anthropology. He graduated in Political Science from Presidency College, standing 2nd in Calcutta University. He also studied at the University of Cambridge and the University of Sussex in the UK.\n<ref>{{cite web|last1=UNESCO|title=Tagore, Neruda and C\u00e9saire|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/culture/themes/dialogue/tagore-neruda-and-cesaire/networks-and-partners/international-sponsoring-committee/jawhar-sircar/}}</ref>\n\n==Career in Administration==\n\nAfter joining the Indian Administrative Service (IAS) in 1975<ref>{{cite web|title=Civil List Of IAS Officers|url=http://wbpar.gov.in/CommonUser/IAS_list.aspx|website=wbpar|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> in West Bengal (India), he held several postings in the districts of Burdwan and 24 Parganas where he made a name for himself in tackling very difficult problems including communal riots. In 1980, he took on the coal mafia of the Asansol-Raniganj belt. He had to face 27 different contempt cases filed by the Coal Mafia in the high court, but he saw to the end of this 'mafia raj', at least till his departure.\n\nHe handled the huge manpower management of pilgrims during the Ganga Sagar Mela (which is second only to the Kumbh Mela) for two successive years.  He had a one-year stint in Handicrafts and Handlooms, where he helped revive some of Bengal's traditional skills and was instrumental in saving/re-introducing the dying forms of \u2018Baluchari Sarees\u2019 and Traditional \u2018Kantha-stitch\u2019 textiles of the State. In 1984 he became the state's youngest Director of Industries; during his stint here he vigorously promoted Small and Medium Enterprises.\n\nHe next took charge as District Magistrate and District Collector of Burdwan (Barddhaman), one of the most populous and problematic districts of India, which covered Raniganj coal field area, Asansol and Durgapur, as also the richest agrarian belt of the State. He also served as private secretary to the commerce minister underwent specialised training in Foreign Trade in NY World Trade Institute and the IIFT in Delhi.\n\nIn 1986, he moved to New Delhi, and served as Director, the Ministry of Commerce, Government of India, looking after Agricultural Exports and Foreign Trade with specific regions like Africa and East Europe.\n\nOn his return to West Bengal in 1992, he first served as Secretary of the Food Processing Industries Department where he could help start several industry. He took over as the Ist IAS Commissioner of Stamp Duties and was instrumental in introducing Circle Rates for the basis of registration and stamp duty.  This brought in an additional source of revenue to the State which has gone up in leaps and bounds since then he broke new records in revenue collection in sales tax and property duties against veritable opposition from builders'lobby. After this, he moved on to become the Secretary in the Finance Department looking after Expenditure.,<ref>{{cite web|title=Innovation is the Mantra of Success|url=http://currentnews.in/innovation-is-my-mantra/}}</ref> he was appointed Sales Tax Commissioner of West Bengal where he could secure the highest rate of growth in the 1990s.\n\nHe was selected as the Chief Electoral Officer of West Bengal, where he conducted the 1998 and 1999 Parliamentary Elections during challenging periods, which included the devastating 1999 floods; many voters got to exercise their franchise in makeshift polling stations that were innovatively set up on boats. He was specially commended by the Election Commission of India for the successful conduct of two Parliamentary Elections.\n\nIn 2000, he was selected as Industry Secretary of West Bengal, and he embarked on the uphill task of turning around the industrial climate and image of West Bengal, which he could accomplish during his tenure.\n\nIn 2003, he was entrusted with the task of modernizing the Higher and Technical education sectors in West Bengal, as Principal Secretary. In the delivery of his responsibilities, he introduced several wide-ranging reforms, and had to confront powerful unions and other entrenched opposition.\n\n[[File:Jawhar Sircar with Veteran Actress Sharmila Tagore.JPG|thumb|left|Jawhar Sircar with [[Sharmila Tagore|Veteran Actress Sharmila Tagore]]]]\n\nIn May, 2006, Sircar was called to the Government of India in New Delhi, on promotion as Additional Secretary and Development Commissioner for Micro, Small and Medium Enterprises (MSME), a term that he helped introduce through a new Act of Parliament. He is known as the pioneer of 'Cluster Development', as well as for grass-roots financing of tiny industries, including Micro Finance and also for initiating several reforms in the sector.\n<ref>{{cite web|last1=MSME|title=Focus on skill development in small scale sector|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/focus-on-skill-development-in-small-scale-sector/article1886789.ece|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2008,<ref>{{cite web|title=Invited speakers|url=http://www.ehu.eus/en/web/india-bilbao-congress2015/speakers#2|website=ehu|accessdate=1 May 2008}}</ref> he was elevated as Secretary to Government of India, and moved on to head the Ministry of Culture,<ref>{{cite web|title=jawhar sircar to take charge as CEO|url=http://dxersguide.blogspot.in/2012/02/jawhar-sircar-to-take-charge-as-prasar.html|website=dxersguide|accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref> where he served as its longest-serving Secretary till early 2012.He initiated long-pending reforms and took up the modernization of museums, archives, and libraries. He is credited with introducing many new programmes to assist cultural organizations and their expressions. Jawhar Sircar was successful in forging a significant number of cultural partnerships between India and other countries,<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Pelletier & Jawhar Sircar inaugurate the exhibition \u2018The Poetry of Purpose\u2019|url=http://firstreport.in/michael-pelletier-jawhar-sircar-inaugurate-the-exhibition-the-poetry-of-purpose/|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> and among his major credits are the Anish Kapoor exhibition from the UK and the holding of seven unique overseas<ref>{{cite news|title=Prasar Bharati signs MoU with Germany's DW to distribute DD overseas|url=http://www.exchange4media.com/tv/prasar-bharati-signs-mou-with-germanys-dw-to-distribute-dd-overseas_56849.html|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> exhibitions of the original paintings of Rabindra Nath Tagore which had not left India shores for more than 80 years.\n\nHe also had two short stints as acting Secretary, Ministry of Information & Broadcasting, Government of India.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar sircar|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/content/editorial/news/jawahar-sircar-new-ib-secretary}}</ref>\n\nSircar has worked in the fields of Finance, Commerce<ref>{{cite news|title=Print media not making money online\", Jawhar Sircar, CEO, Prasar Bharati|url=http://www.iamwire.com/2013/04/%E2%80%9Cprint-media-not-making-money-online%E2%80%9D-jawhar-sircar-ceo-prasar-bharati/8300|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> and Industries for 17 of his 38 years in public service, where he has managed large corporations, including the multibillion-dollar Haldia Petrochemicals.\n\nOn the other hand, he has also worked in the field of public communication: i.e., in Education, Culture and Media<ref>{{cite web|title=Prasar Bharati appoints 55 persons|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/prasar-bharati-appoints-55-persons-for-posts-in-air-dd-says-chairperson-jawhar-sircar/533365-3.html|website=ibnlive|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref> related assignments, for over 11 years.\n\n==His Association==\n\nJawhar Sircar was a  Member of the Governing Councils of Indian Council of World Affairs (ICWA),<ref>{{cite web|title=ICWA Members' List|url=http://www.icwa.in/members_council.html|publisher=ICWA}}</ref>  Consortium for Educational Communication,<ref>{{cite web|title=Governing Council Members of CEC|url=http://cec.nic.in/Governance/Pages/Governing-Council.aspx|publisher=Consortium of Educational Communication}}</ref> Film & Television Institute of India<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ftiindia.com/management.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518052018/http://ftiindia.com/management.html |archive-date=18 May 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and also  Trustee/GB Member of IIM (India Institute of Management), Kolkata,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Ahiritola Sutanuti Heritage Trust|url=http://www.ahiritolasutanutiheritagetrust.com/artexhibition.html|website=Ahiritola Sutanuti Heritage Trust|accessdate=23 March 2014}}</ref> Victoria Memorial Museum, Indian Museum, National Museum, National Library, National School of Drama, IGNCA, the Three National Akademies,etc.\n\nHe has also served on the National Advisory Council of Spic Macay.,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indiaeducationdiary.in/ShowIIT.asp?newsid=34716 |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222094249/http://indiaeducationdiary.in/ShowIIT.asp?newsid=34716 |archive-date=22 December 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and was nominated on the National Executive Council of CII. He had also been on the Board of Governors of Media Research Users Council (MRUC), Mumbai, which does research/surveys for readership, viewership and listenership of various media for advertising.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar|url=http://mruc.net/?q=Current-Board-of-Governors|publisher=MRUC}}</ref> He had been on the Advisory Board of CEMPD, Kolkata ( Centre for Environmental Management and Participatory Development.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jawhar Sircar|url=http://www.cempd.com/index.php?view=cms&id=1| publisher=cempd}}</ref> Sircar has also been a Trustee Member of PSBT<ref>{{cite web|title=public service broadcasting in India|last1=PSBT|first1=New Delhi|url=http://www.psbt.org/}}</ref> (Public Service Broadcasting Trust) from 2012 to 2016.\n\n==Other Interests==\n\nJawhar Sircar was Vice President of the All India Tennis Association,<ref>{{cite web|title=Jawhar Sircar|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/tennis/anil-khanna-elected-aita-president/article3536738.ece|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref>  and served as the President of India's pioneering Children's Little Theatre. \nSircar has also been a Trustee Member of PSBT<ref>{{cite web|title=public service broadcasting in India|last1=PSBT|first1=New Delhi|url=http://www.psbt.org/}}</ref> (Public Service Broadcasting Trust) from 2012 to 2016.\n\nHe is a Life Member of the 240-year-old Asiatic Society, Indian National Confederation and Academy of Anthropologists,<ref>{{cite web|title=Jawhar Sircar|url=http://www.incaa.net/membership.html|publisher=The Hindu the India International Centre, the Indian Anthropological Society,Indian National Trust for Arts}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar in National Gallery of Modern Art|url=http://www.artnewsnviews.com/view-article.php?article=jawahar-sircar&iid=21&articleid=523|accessdate=26 June 2011}}</ref> & Cultural Heritage,  Bangiya Sahitya Parishad,  Indian History Congress and several other well-known institutions.\n\nHe was the moving spirit behind the Kolkata<ref>{{cite news|title=Book-crazy Kolkata ready for litfest\u2019s big-bang start|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/Book-crazy-Kolkata-ready-for-litfests-big-bang-start/articleshow/45877276.cms|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> International Film Festival from 1997 to 2005, and has organized several film and media related programmes, with participation of many countries.\n\nSircar<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr. Jawhar Sircar|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=170985618&privcapId=13484380&previousCapId=13484380&previousTitle=Prasar%20Bharati%20Broadcasting%20Corp.|website=bloomberg|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> was instrumental in the management of world's largest Book Fair, in terms of attendance, i.e., the Kolkata Book Fair in its early years.\n\n== Awards ==\n\n[[File:Jawhar Sircar with Honorable Minister Of Environment Mr. Prakesh Javadekar.JPG|thumb|Jawhar Sircar with [[Prakash Javadekar|Honorable Minister of Human Resource Development Mr. Prakash Javadekar]]]]\n\n*  Biman Bihari Majumdar Award for History and Politics by Asiatic Society \n*  British Museum's Silver Medal for Promoting Museum Reforms in 2011\n*  Nihar Ranjan Ray Smarak Samman in 2018 by Sanskriti Sansad, Kolkata\n*  Silver Medal of GoI for Extraordinary Service in Census Operations in 1982\n*  Best CEO Award in 2013(Two years after joining PB)<ref>{{cite web|title=Best CEO|url=http://airddfamily.blogspot.in/2014/01/jawhar-sircar-ceo-prasar-bharati-has.html}}</ref>\n*  Maulana Jameel Ilyasi Excellency Award \u2013 August, 2013<ref>{{cite news|title=MJI Excellence Award 2013|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-08-21/news/41437586_1_rsm-contributions-fields}}</ref>\n*  News Television Network CEO of the Year ENBA 2013 Award<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar, CEO, Prasar Bharati has been given the News Television Network CEO of the Year ENBA 2013 Award|url=http://airddfamily.blogspot.in/2014/01/jawhar-sircar-ceo-prasar-bharati-has.html|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n*  Institute Of Directors Distinguished Fellowship Award in 2014\n*  Corporate Broadcaster of the Year, Award by Calcutta Management Association<ref>{{cite news|title=Corporate Broadcaster of the Year|url=http://airddfamily.blogspot.in/2016/03/jawhar-sircar-ceo-pb-receives-award-for.html|agency=CMA|publisher=PB Parivar}}</ref> \n* In 2015 Digital Studio Broadcasting & Production Magazine had placed him among the 10 most important people in the broadcasting industry.<ref>{{cite web|title=Digital Studio|url=http://digitalstudioindia.com/?p=58/}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jawhar Sircar}}\n{{wikiquote|Jawhar Sircar}}\n* {{official website|http://jawharsircar.com/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sircar, Jawhar}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Queens' College, Cambridge]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox  person\n| name       = ''Jawhar Sircar''\n| image      =\n|caption = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1952|03|22}}\n|birth_place = [[Calcutta, India]]\n|nationality = [[India]]n\n| education       = [[St. Xavier's Collegiate School|St. Xavier\u2019s School]] <br>[[Presidency College, Calcutta|Presidency College]]<br>[[Calcutta University]]<br>[[University of Sussex]]<br>[[Queens\u2019 College, Cambridge]]\n| notable_works  =\n| spouse = Nandita Sircar\n| children = Shaurya Sircar\n| website = {{URL|http://jawharsircar.com}}\n}}\n'''Jawhar Sircar''' (born March 22, 1952) is a public intellectual based out of Kolkata who is known for his writings <ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar Articles|url=https://thewire.in/author/jawhar-sircar}}</ref> and public talks at eminent institutions of national and international repute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar In News|url=https://www.orfonline.org/research/should-india-promote-democracy-through-foreign-policy-50828/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar In News|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/social-reformer-ishwar-chandra-vidyasagar-championed-widow-remarriage/story-iifd4ee3RDI9hamGdDvVBJ.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar In News|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/dissected-bengali-culture/cid/1669818}}</ref> He is currently Chairman of the Board of Governors of the Centre for Studies in Social Sciences, Kolkata, which is the premier Social Science research institution. He is also on the Governing bodies of Universities and Educational institutes.\n\nThe Asiatic Society, established in 1784 in Kolkata as the Royal Asiatic Society, awarded him the Dr Biman Behari Memorial Lectureship in 2017 \u201cfor his outstanding contribution the history and political thought\u201d. He was also selected for the Nihar Ranjan Smarak Samman by the Sanskriti Sansad of Kolkata.\n\nEarlier, in 2006, eminent historian, late Tapan Raichaudhuri of Oxford university dedicated a whole article in Bengal's journal of intellect and culture, ''Desh'', where he discussed his first research work ''The Construction of the Hindu Identity in Medieval Western Bengal: The Role of Popular Cults (2005)'' and commended him \"for his exceptional analytical power and depth of knowledge in diverse fields\u201d <ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar Articles|url=http://jawharsircar.com/articles_Books_Monographs.html}}</ref>\n\nAs a civil servant, he had the unique honour of being commended in public by the prime minister of India as \"a most distinguished and knowledgeable civil servant\", which is on record. In 2011, the British Museum conveyed its \u201cesteem and gratitude\u201d to Jawhar Sircar \u201cfor his outstanding contribution to cultural cooperation between the Republic of India and the United Kingdom\u201d and conferred a medal on him. He combined excellence in his profession as an administrator with a passion for knowledge and adroitly managed to balance both sides.\n\n== Summary ==\n\nJawhar Sircar (22 March 1952) is an Indian civil servant <ref>{{cite web|title=Jawhar sircar|url=http://www.psbt.org/general/trustees|website=psbt|accessdate=1 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423065307/http://www.psbt.org/general/trustees|archivedate=23 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with 41 years experience, and last served as Chief Executive Officer of Prasar Bharati( Doordarshan & All India Radio) <ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar critiques the current state of journalism in print, TV|url=http://www.exchange4media.com/58960_jawhar-sircar-critiques-the-current-state-of-journalism-in-print-tv.html|accessdate=3 February 2015|publisher=Exchange 4 Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Prasar Bharti CEO Jawhar Sircar to attend KLF\u2019s inaugural ceremony|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/terrestrial/prasar-bharti-ceo-jawhar-sircar-to-attend-klf-s-inaugural-ceremony-150203|accessdate=3 February 2015|publisher=Indian Television}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar sweeps over Public Broadcasters session at FICCI|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/biz/radio/air/jawhar-sircar-sweeps-over-public-broadcasters-session-ficci-2015-150326|accessdate=2015-03-26|publisher=RM Biz}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The travails of being a Prasar Bharati CEO|url=http://www.televisionpost.com/ficci-frames/the-travails-of-being-a-prasar-bharati-ceo/|accessdate=27 March 2015|publisher=Television post}}</ref> of Prasar Bharati<ref>{{cite news|title=Fast forward at DD News|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/fast-forward-at-dd-news/1073705/|accessdate=14 February 2013|publisher=The Indian Express}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Watch DD\u2019s viewer-friendly avatar|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1130205/jsp/nation/story_16524133.jsp#.VTY31NKqqkq|accessdate=February 5, 2013|publisher=Indian publisher}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Propaganda darshan|url=http://blogs.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/TheSiegeWithin/propaganda-darshan/|accessdate=February 17, 2013|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Launching of Virtual Museum of Indian Art & Culture|url=http://news.webindia123.com/news/printer.asp?story=/news/Articles/India/20120523/1990054.html|accessdate=May 23, 2012|publisher=Web India}}</ref> (Doordarshan<ref>{{cite news|title=Prasar Bharati CEO puts lid over DD row|url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/prasar-bharati-ceo-puts-lid-over-dd-row/|accessdate=5 May 2014|publisher=The Free Press Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Doordarshan\u2019s New Look Attract Profits|url=http://india.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/02/22/state-run-doordarshan-plans-an-overhaul/?_r=2|accessdate=22 February 2013|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Don\u2019t let Doordarshan die|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/opinion/dont-let-doordarshan-die/article4425191.ece|accessdate=17 February 2013|publisher=the hindu businessline}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Doordarshan may go BBC way|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/newdelhi/doordarshan-may--go-bbc-way/article1-1005937.aspx|accessdate=4 February 2013|publisher=Hindustan Times}}</ref> & All India Radio<ref>{{cite news|title=AIR expresses regrets over anti-Pak re-tweets|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/air-expresses-regrets-over-antipak-retweets/article6902872.ece|accessdate=17 February 2015|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AIR needs fresh, young talent: Prasar Bharati CEO|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/air-needs-fresh-young-talent-prasar-bharati-ceo/article6773724.ece|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=JAWHAR SIRCAR: FUTURE OF PRASAR BHARATI LIES IN FM RADIO, AND INTERNET RADIO|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/biz/radio/air/jawhar-sircar-future-prasar-bharati-lies-fm-radio-and-internet-radio|accessdate=13 November 2014|publisher=Radio and Music}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Classical music: Who picks up the tab?|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Classical-music-Who-picks-up-the-tab/articleshow/45408154.cms|accessdate=8 December 2014|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref>).\n\nBefore this, he was  Secretary of the Ministry of Culture,<ref>{{cite web|title=Jawhar Sircar, Secretary, Ministry of Culture, Government of India in Kolkata, West Bengal, India. (Jawhar Sarcar, IAS)|url=http://www.indiatodayimages.com/indiatodayimages/buyimage-jawhar-sircar,-secretary,-ministry-of-culture-4098637.html|website=India Today}}</ref> Government of India from late 2008 to February 2012, where he reported directly to the Prime Minister for most of his tenure.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manmohan's dinner diplomacy a hit with Obama|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/manmohans-dinner-diplomacy-a-hit-with-obama/article872989.ece}}</ref> He resigned, to take over his current position, for which he was chosen by an eminent panel led by the Vice President of India and Supreme Court Judge.  \tAs Culture<ref>{{cite web|title=Seminar Report|url=http://matrimandirdelhi.com/legacy-of-swami-vivekananda.htm|website=matri mandir delhi|accessdate=1 May 2013}}</ref> Secretary, he initiated long-pending reforms and took up the modernization of museums, archives, and libraries for which he was awarded the British Museum Medal.<ref>{{cite web|title=JAWHAR SIRCAR secretary culture|url=http://www.ignca.nic.in/ifla2010/IFLA_PDF/JAWHAR_SIRCAR_secretary_culture.pdf|publisher=IGNCA}}</ref>\n\nAs CEO,Prasar Bharati,<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar set to become Prasar Bharati CEO|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/jawhar-sircar-set-to-become-prasar-bharati-ceo/article2904179.ece|accessdate=18 February 2012|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref> he supervised India's public service broadcaster, which is among the largest such networks in the world and cover well over a billion people, through 483 stations of All India Radio<ref>{{cite news|title=Vividh Bharati moves to FM platform in Kolkata|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/Vividh-Bharati-moves-to-FM-platform-in-Kolkata/articleshow/45654448.cms|accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref> (AIR) & Doordarshan <ref>{{cite news|title=Doordarshan, China's CCTV sign MoU for co-productions, programme exchange|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-05-15/news/62192267_1_co-productions-cctv-doordarshan|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Doordarshan & China\u2019s CCTV ink MoU for co-production|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/terrestrial/doordarshan-china-s-cctv-ink-mou-for-co-production-150516|accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref>(TV).  As a large orthodox organization of government servants, it is difficult to modernize, but Sircar has been able to break new grounds and introduce digital technologies and cut down obsolescence.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prasar Bharati at the crossroads|url=http://www.thehoot.org/web/Prasar-Bharati-at-the-crossroads/6980-1-1-19-true.html|publisher=The Hoot}}</ref>  He has received three Awards for this in three years.  He has been elected as Vice President of the world's largest Public TV and Radio organization,<ref>{{cite news|title=Compromise and continuity is the essence of Indian culture|url=http://theindianeye.net/india-talks/compromise-and-continuity-is-the-essence-of-indian-culture-jawhar-sircar-37544.html|agency=India Eye|publisher=Spain}}</ref> the Asia Pacific Broadcasting Union,<ref>{{cite news|title=Prasar Bharati CEO Jawahar Sircar elected ABU vice president|url=http://www.exchange4media.com/tv/prasar-bharati-ceo-jawahar-sircar-elected-abu-vice-president_57960.html|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> on which 67 nations are represented.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prasar Bharati CEO Jawhar Sircar elected VP of Asia Broadcasting Union|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Prasar-Bharati-CEO-Jawhar-Sircar-elected-VP-of-Asia-Broadcasting-Union/articleshow/44966349.cms|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref> He is currently Chairman of the Board of Governors of the prestigious Centre for Studies in Social Science, Kolkata, a premier research and teaching institute.\n\n== Academics & Publications ==\n\nHe has been active in research even while working full-time in administration. He has published numerous articles on cultural,<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar at remembering-dadaji |url=http://www.thestatesman.com/news/supplements/remembering-dadaji/117279.html|publisher=DK Roy Memorial}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar at ASU|url=http://university.apeejay.edu/docs/ASU-MediaFestival-Schedule.pdf|publisher=Apeejay Media Fest}}</ref> historical<ref>{{cite news |title=Jawhar Sircar|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1160113/jsp/jharkhand/story_63546.jsp#.VrMGZ9IrLIU}}</ref> and anthropological subjects for several years. He has published research papers on the subjects of history,<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar gets-emotional|url=http://www.sarkarimirror.com/jawhar-sircar-ceo-prasar-bharti-gets-emotional-at-an-address-gathering-of-his-late-father-nil-ratan-sircar/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Who will donate if you don\u2019t show the greed of virtue ABP,Kolkata|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/who-will-donate-if-you-dont-show-the-greed-of-virtue-1.136780|accessdate=21 April 2015|publisher=Ananda Bazar}}</ref> culture,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Telegraph |first1=Kolkata |title=Paper flowers, Coca Cola, and a crown of thorns |url= http://www.telegraphindia.com/1141225/jsp/opinion/story_5123.jsp#.VPgXr3yUeOY}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jawhar Sircar in CII |url= http://www.ciibigpicture.com/pdf/Programme-CII%20BigPicture-September-2014.pdf |publisher= CII}}</ref> media<ref>{{cite news |title= Be Open Minded and Work Collaboratively |url= http://uohherald.commuoh.in/be-open-minded-and-work-collaboratively-jawahar-sircar/}}</ref>  & society.<ref>{{cite news |title= A Valentine story |url= http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/a-valentine-story/|accessdate=14 February 2015|publisher=Indian Publishers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Raja Ram Mohun Roy|url=http://www.topictimes.com/videos/people/jawhar-sircar-on-film---in-search-of-the-rajah-full-XKCV1yeUEbE.html}}</ref>\n\nHe has also delivered talks on the subjects of history,<ref>{{cite news|title=Popular Culture|url=http://calcuttadebatingcircle.com/day-wise_events.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Presentation given entitled Competition, Conflict and Harmony : Vividh Bharati and the emergence of a Supra-National identity in India, Jadunath Museum and Resource Centre, Kolkata|url=http://www.victoriamemorial-cal.org/archived_spevents.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Keynote Address of Closing Ceremony of Retrospective of Prosenjit Chatterjee, Indian Habitat Centre, New Delhi|url=https://prosenjitblog.wordpress.com/2015/10/01/it-was-the-closing-day-of-the-retrospective-an-evening-so-rewarding-and-promising/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Curious tales from a city\u2019s history|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1131117/jsp/calcutta/story_17577198.jsp#.VPg6vCyr_K8|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref> culture<ref>{{cite news|title=Chairperson in the book discussion \"In the name of the Goddess\"  By Tapati Guha Thakurta|url=http://www.delhievents.com/2015/09/in-name-of-goddess-durga-pujas-of.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Book Launch Pigeons of the Dome written by Rakshanda Jalil, Niyogi Books, New Delhi|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/books/secularism-and-communalism-are-conjoined-twins/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Book Launch Golpoguche Natyarupe of Soumitra Chatterjee on Tagore\u2019s plays and stories , Kolkata|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1151015/jsp/t2/story_47960.jsp#.VjH6GyWqqko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rooting for our roots|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1140324/jsp/calcutta/story_18112250.jsp#.VPg5yyyr_K9}}</ref> and media.<ref>{{cite news|title=How Radio & TV Brought A Nation Together - Jawhar Sircar CEO PB Spoke at Berlin.|url=http://airddfamily.blogspot.in/2015/10/how-radio-tv-brought-nation-together.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=CII big picture|url=http://www.ciibigpicture.com/pdf/CII_Newsletter_July_2014_final.pdf|website=CII}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Prasar Bharati plans to enter the european market|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/terrestrial/prasar-bharati-plans-to-enter-the-european-market-says-sircar-140701}}</ref> His monograph: ''The Construction of the Hindu Identity in Medieval Western Bengal: The Role of Popular Cults'' was well received in India and abroad.\n\nHis writings are both available in Bangla<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bazaar|first1=Anand|title=\u0987\u09b8\u09cd\u099f\u09be\u09b0\u09c7\u09b0 \u099c\u09a8\u09cd\u09ae \u0995\u09bf\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09c1 \u0996\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09b8\u09cd\u099f\u09c7\u09b0 \u0985\u09a8\u09c7\u0995 \u0986\u0997\u09c7|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/easter-took-birth-before-chirst-1.130042|work=Jawhar Sircar}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bazaar|first1=Anand|title=\u0998\u09a1\u09bc\u09bf \u09a7\u09b0\u09c7 \u2018\u09b9\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09aa\u09bf \u09a8\u09bf\u0989 \u0987\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0\u2019 \u09a8\u09af\u09bc|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/unity-in-diversity-on-the-eve-of-different-types-of-happy-new-year-1.134549|work=Jawhar Sircar}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bazaar|first1=Anand|title=\u2018\u09a8\u09bf\u09b0\u09cd\u09ac\u09cb\u09a7 \u0986\u099a\u09b0\u09a3 \u0986\u099b\u09c7 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09ad\u09c2\u09a4 \u09aa\u09b0\u09bf\u09ae\u09be\u09a3\u09c7\u2019|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/%E0%A6%A8-%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%AC-%E0%A6%A7-%E0%A6%86%E0%A6%9A%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%A3-%E0%A6%86%E0%A6%9B-%E0%A6%AA-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%AD-%E0%A6%A4-%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%AE-%E0%A6%A3-1.120726}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bazaar|first1=Anand|title=\u09b6\u09bf\u09ac\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ae\u09a4\u09cb \u09ac\u09b0 \u099a\u09be\u0987\u09a4\u09c7 \u09b6\u09c7\u0996\u09be\u09a8\u09cb \u09b9\u09b2 \u0995\u09c7\u09a8|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/\u09b6-\u09ac-\u09b0-\u09ae\u09a4-\u09ac\u09b0-\u099a-\u0987\u09a4-\u09b6-\u0996-\u09a8-\u09b9\u09b2-\u0995-\u09a8-1.115980}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bazaar|first1=Anand|title=\u0985\u09a8\u09c7\u0995 \u09ad\u09be\u09b0\u09a4, \u098f\u0995 \u09ae\u0995\u09b0 \u09b8\u0982\u0995\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/\u0985\u09a8-\u0995-\u09ad-\u09b0\u09a4-\u098f\u0995-\u09ae\u0995\u09b0-\u09b8-\u0995-\u09b0-\u09a8-\u09a4-1.105505}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bazaar|first1=Anand|title=\u09a6\u09bf\u09b2\u09cd\u09b2\u09bf\u09b0 \u09a6\u09b0\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf? \u0996\u09c1\u0981\u099c\u09bf \u0996\u09c1\u0981\u099c\u09bf \u09a8\u09be\u09b0\u09bf|url=http://www.anandabazar.com/editorial/\u09a6-\u09b2-\u09b2-\u09b0-\u09a6\u09b0\u09ac-\u09b0-\u09ac-\u0999-\u09b2-\u0996-\u099c-\u0996-\u099c-\u09a8-\u09b0-1.92271}}</ref> as well as English newspapers.<ref>{{cite news|title='Salvaging and sanitising\u2019 classical dance|url=http://www.asianage.com/dance/salvaging-and-sanitising-classical-dance-835|publisher=Asian Age}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n[[File:While Signing an MoU with Chinese Counterpart as Hon'ble PM Narender Modi looks on.jpg|thumb|While Signing an MoU with Chinese Counterpart as Hon'ble PM [[Narendra Modi]] looks on]]\n\nJawhar Sircar studied at St. Xavier's School, Presidency College and Calcutta University - all in Kolkata.\nHe did his Masters in Ancient Indian History and Culture from Calcutta University and a second Masters in Sociology, with Social Anthropology. He graduated in Political Science from Presidency College, standing 2nd in Calcutta University. He also studied at the University of Cambridge and the University of Sussex in the UK.\n<ref>{{cite web|last1=UNESCO|title=Tagore, Neruda and C\u00e9saire|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/culture/themes/dialogue/tagore-neruda-and-cesaire/networks-and-partners/international-sponsoring-committee/jawhar-sircar/}}</ref>\n\n==Career in Administration==\n\nAfter joining the Indian Administrative Service (IAS) in 1975<ref>{{cite web|title=Civil List Of IAS Officers|url=http://wbpar.gov.in/CommonUser/IAS_list.aspx|website=wbpar|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> in West Bengal (India), he held several postings in the districts of Burdwan and 24 Parganas where he made a name for himself in tackling very difficult problems including communal riots. In 1980, he took on the coal mafia of the Asansol-Raniganj belt. He had to face 27 different contempt cases filed by the Coal Mafia in the high court, but he saw to the end of this 'mafia raj', at least till his departure.\n\nHe handled the huge manpower management of pilgrims during the Ganga Sagar Mela (which is second only to the Kumbh Mela) for two successive years.  He had a one-year stint in Handicrafts and Handlooms, where he helped revive some of Bengal's traditional skills and was instrumental in saving/re-introducing the dying forms of \u2018Baluchari Sarees\u2019 and Traditional \u2018Kantha-stitch\u2019 textiles of the State. In 1984 he became the state's youngest Director of Industries; during his stint here he vigorously promoted Small and Medium Enterprises.\n\nHe next took charge as District Magistrate and District Collector of Burdwan (Barddhaman), one of the most populous and problematic districts of India, which covered Raniganj coal field area, Asansol and Durgapur, as also the richest agrarian belt of the State. He also served as private secretary to the commerce minister underwent specialised training in Foreign Trade in NY World Trade Institute and the IIFT in Delhi.\n\nIn 1986, he moved to New Delhi, and served as Director, the Ministry of Commerce, Government of India, looking after Agricultural Exports and Foreign Trade with specific regions like Africa and East Europe.\n\nOn his return to West Bengal in 1992, he first served as Secretary of the Food Processing Industries Department where he could help start several industry. He took over as the Ist IAS Commissioner of Stamp Duties and was instrumental in introducing Circle Rates for the basis of registration and stamp duty.  This brought in an additional source of revenue to the State which has gone up in leaps and bounds since then he broke new records in revenue collection in sales tax and property duties against veritable opposition from builders'lobby. After this, he moved on to become the Secretary in the Finance Department looking after Expenditure.,<ref>{{cite web|title=Innovation is the Mantra of Success|url=http://currentnews.in/innovation-is-my-mantra/}}</ref> he was appointed Sales Tax Commissioner of West Bengal where he could secure the highest rate of growth in the 1990s.\n\nHe was selected as the Chief Electoral Officer of West Bengal, where he conducted the 1998 and 1999 Parliamentary Elections during challenging periods, which included the devastating 1999 floods; many voters got to exercise their franchise in makeshift polling stations that were innovatively set up on boats. He was specially commended by the Election Commission of India for the successful conduct of two Parliamentary Elections.\n\nIn 2000, he was selected as Industry Secretary of West Bengal, and he embarked on the uphill task of turning around the industrial climate and image of West Bengal, which he could accomplish during his tenure.\n\nIn 2003, he was entrusted with the task of modernizing the Higher and Technical education sectors in West Bengal, as Principal Secretary. In the delivery of his responsibilities, he introduced several wide-ranging reforms, and had to confront powerful unions and other entrenched opposition.\n\n[[File:Jawhar Sircar with Veteran Actress Sharmila Tagore.JPG|thumb|left|Jawhar Sircar with [[Sharmila Tagore|Veteran Actress Sharmila Tagore]]]]\n\nIn May, 2006, Sircar was called to the Government of India in New Delhi, on promotion as Additional Secretary and Development Commissioner for Micro, Small and Medium Enterprises (MSME), a term that he helped introduce through a new Act of Parliament. He is known as the pioneer of 'Cluster Development', as well as for grass-roots financing of tiny industries, including Micro Finance and also for initiating several reforms in the sector.\n<ref>{{cite web|last1=MSME|title=Focus on skill development in small scale sector|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/focus-on-skill-development-in-small-scale-sector/article1886789.ece|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2008,<ref>{{cite web|title=Invited speakers|url=http://www.ehu.eus/en/web/india-bilbao-congress2015/speakers#2|website=ehu|accessdate=1 May 2008}}</ref> he was elevated as Secretary to Government of India, and moved on to head the Ministry of Culture,<ref>{{cite web|title=jawhar sircar to take charge as CEO|url=http://dxersguide.blogspot.in/2012/02/jawhar-sircar-to-take-charge-as-prasar.html|website=dxersguide|accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref> where he served as its longest-serving Secretary till early 2012.He initiated long-pending reforms and took up the modernization of museums, archives, and libraries. He is credited with introducing many new programmes to assist cultural organizations and their expressions. Jawhar Sircar was successful in forging a significant number of cultural partnerships between India and other countries,<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Pelletier & Jawhar Sircar inaugurate the exhibition \u2018The Poetry of Purpose\u2019|url=http://firstreport.in/michael-pelletier-jawhar-sircar-inaugurate-the-exhibition-the-poetry-of-purpose/|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> and among his major credits are the Anish Kapoor exhibition from the UK and the holding of seven unique overseas<ref>{{cite news|title=Prasar Bharati signs MoU with Germany's DW to distribute DD overseas|url=http://www.exchange4media.com/tv/prasar-bharati-signs-mou-with-germanys-dw-to-distribute-dd-overseas_56849.html|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> exhibitions of the original paintings of Rabindra Nath Tagore which had not left India shores for more than 80 years.\n\nHe also had two short stints as acting Secretary, Ministry of Information & Broadcasting, Government of India.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar sircar|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/content/editorial/news/jawahar-sircar-new-ib-secretary}}</ref>\n\nSircar has worked in the fields of Finance, Commerce<ref>{{cite news|title=Print media not making money online\", Jawhar Sircar, CEO, Prasar Bharati|url=http://www.iamwire.com/2013/04/%E2%80%9Cprint-media-not-making-money-online%E2%80%9D-jawhar-sircar-ceo-prasar-bharati/8300|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> and Industries for 17 of his 38 years in public service, where he has managed large corporations, including the multibillion-dollar Haldia Petrochemicals.\n\nOn the other hand, he has also worked in the field of public communication: i.e., in Education, Culture and Media<ref>{{cite web|title=Prasar Bharati appoints 55 persons|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/prasar-bharati-appoints-55-persons-for-posts-in-air-dd-says-chairperson-jawhar-sircar/533365-3.html|website=ibnlive|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref> related assignments, for over 11 years.\n\n==His Association==\n\nJawhar Sircar was a  Member of the Governing Councils of Indian Council of World Affairs (ICWA),<ref>{{cite web|title=ICWA Members' List|url=http://www.icwa.in/members_council.html|publisher=ICWA}}</ref>  Consortium for Educational Communication,<ref>{{cite web|title=Governing Council Members of CEC|url=http://cec.nic.in/Governance/Pages/Governing-Council.aspx|publisher=Consortium of Educational Communication}}</ref> Film & Television Institute of India<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ftiindia.com/management.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518052018/http://ftiindia.com/management.html |archive-date=18 May 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and also  Trustee/GB Member of IIM (India Institute of Management), Kolkata,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Ahiritola Sutanuti Heritage Trust|url=http://www.ahiritolasutanutiheritagetrust.com/artexhibition.html|website=Ahiritola Sutanuti Heritage Trust|accessdate=23 March 2014}}</ref> Victoria Memorial Museum, Indian Museum, National Museum, National Library, National School of Drama, IGNCA, the Three National Akademies,etc.\n\nHe has also served on the National Advisory Council of Spic Macay.,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indiaeducationdiary.in/ShowIIT.asp?newsid=34716 |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222094249/http://indiaeducationdiary.in/ShowIIT.asp?newsid=34716 |archive-date=22 December 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and was nominated on the National Executive Council of CII. He had also been on the Board of Governors of Media Research Users Council (MRUC), Mumbai, which does research/surveys for readership, viewership and listenership of various media for advertising.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar|url=http://mruc.net/?q=Current-Board-of-Governors|publisher=MRUC}}</ref> He had been on the Advisory Board of CEMPD, Kolkata ( Centre for Environmental Management and Participatory Development.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jawhar Sircar|url=http://www.cempd.com/index.php?view=cms&id=1| publisher=cempd}}</ref> Sircar has also been a Trustee Member of PSBT<ref>{{cite web|title=public service broadcasting in India|last1=PSBT|first1=New Delhi|url=http://www.psbt.org/}}</ref> (Public Service Broadcasting Trust) from 2012 to 2016.\n\n==Other Interests==\n\nJawhar Sircar was Vice President of the All India Tennis Association,<ref>{{cite web|title=Jawhar Sircar|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/tennis/anil-khanna-elected-aita-president/article3536738.ece|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref>  and served as the President of India's pioneering Children's Little Theatre. \nSircar has also been a Trustee Member of PSBT<ref>{{cite web|title=public service broadcasting in India|last1=PSBT|first1=New Delhi|url=http://www.psbt.org/}}</ref> (Public Service Broadcasting Trust) from 2012 to 2016.\n\nHe is a Life Member of the 240-year-old Asiatic Society, Indian National Confederation and Academy of Anthropologists,<ref>{{cite web|title=Jawhar Sircar|url=http://www.incaa.net/membership.html|publisher=The Hindu the India International Centre, the Indian Anthropological Society,Indian National Trust for Arts}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar in National Gallery of Modern Art|url=http://www.artnewsnviews.com/view-article.php?article=jawahar-sircar&iid=21&articleid=523|accessdate=26 June 2011}}</ref> & Cultural Heritage,  Bangiya Sahitya Parishad,  Indian History Congress and several other well-known institutions.\n\nHe was the moving spirit behind the Kolkata<ref>{{cite news|title=Book-crazy Kolkata ready for litfest\u2019s big-bang start|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/Book-crazy-Kolkata-ready-for-litfests-big-bang-start/articleshow/45877276.cms|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> International Film Festival from 1997 to 2005, and has organized several film and media related programmes, with participation of many countries.\n\nSircar<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr. Jawhar Sircar|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=170985618&privcapId=13484380&previousCapId=13484380&previousTitle=Prasar%20Bharati%20Broadcasting%20Corp.|website=bloomberg|accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> was instrumental in the management of world's largest Book Fair, in terms of attendance, i.e., the Kolkata Book Fair in its early years.\n\n== Awards ==\n\n[[File:Jawhar Sircar with Honorable Minister Of Environment Mr. Prakesh Javadekar.JPG|thumb|Jawhar Sircar with [[Prakash Javadekar|Honorable Minister of Human Resource Development Mr. Prakash Javadekar]]]]\n\n*  Biman Bihari Majumdar Award for History and Politics by Asiatic Society \n*  British Museum's Silver Medal for Promoting Museum Reforms in 2011\n*  Nihar Ranjan Ray Smarak Samman in 2018 by Sanskriti Sansad, Kolkata\n*  Silver Medal of GoI for Extraordinary Service in Census Operations in 1982\n*  Best CEO Award in 2013(Two years after joining PB)<ref>{{cite web|title=Best CEO|url=http://airddfamily.blogspot.in/2014/01/jawhar-sircar-ceo-prasar-bharati-has.html}}</ref>\n*  Maulana Jameel Ilyasi Excellency Award \u2013 August, 2013<ref>{{cite news|title=MJI Excellence Award 2013|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-08-21/news/41437586_1_rsm-contributions-fields}}</ref>\n*  News Television Network CEO of the Year ENBA 2013 Award<ref>{{cite news|title=Jawhar Sircar, CEO, Prasar Bharati has been given the News Television Network CEO of the Year ENBA 2013 Award|url=http://airddfamily.blogspot.in/2014/01/jawhar-sircar-ceo-prasar-bharati-has.html|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n*  Institute Of Directors Distinguished Fellowship Award in 2014\n*  Corporate Broadcaster of the Year, Award by Calcutta Management Association<ref>{{cite news|title=Corporate Broadcaster of the Year|url=http://airddfamily.blogspot.in/2016/03/jawhar-sircar-ceo-pb-receives-award-for.html|agency=CMA|publisher=PB Parivar}}</ref> \n* In 2015 Digital Studio Broadcasting & Production Magazine had placed him among the 10 most important people in the broadcasting industry.<ref>{{cite web|title=Digital Studio|url=http://digitalstudioindia.com/?p=58/}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jawhar Sircar}}\n{{wikiquote|Jawhar Sircar}}\n* {{official website|http://jawharsircar.com/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sircar, Jawhar}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Queens' College, Cambridge]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4053:397:2316::1c9:a8ad", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jawhar_Sircar"}
{"title_page": "Bridget Cleary", "text_new": "{{short description|Irishwoman killed by her husband, fearing her a changeling}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name = Bridget Cleary\n| image = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = Bridget Boland\n| birth_date = {{birth year|1869}}\n| birth_place = Ballyvadlea, [[County Tipperary]], Ireland\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1895|03|15|1869}}\n| death_place = Ballyvadlea, [[County Tipperary]], Ireland\n| occupation = Dressmaker\n| spouse = Michael Cleary (m. 1887-1895, her death)\n}}\n\n'''Bridget Cleary''' (n\u00e9e '''Boland'''; {{lang-ga|Br\u00edd U\u00ed Chl\u00e9irigh}}; c. 1869 \u2013 15 March 1895) was an Irish woman killed by her husband in 1895. Her death is notable for several peculiarities: the stated motive for the crime was her husband's belief that she had been abducted by [[fairy|fairies]] with a [[changeling]] left in her place; he claimed to have slain only the changeling. The gruesome nature of the case \u2014 she was either [[Death by burning|immolated]] while still alive or set on fire immediately following her death \u2014 prompted extensive press coverage. The trial was closely followed by newspapers in both Ireland and [[Great Britain|Britain]].<ref name=\"McCullough-NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE4D91E3AF93BA35753C1A9669C8B63|author=David Willis McCullough|title=The Fairy Defense|work=New York Times|date=8 October 2000|accessdate=23 March 2007}}</ref> As one reviewer commented, nobody, with the possible exception of the presiding judge, thought it was an ordinary murder case.<ref name=\"McCullough-NYT\"/>\n\n==Early life and marriage==\nCleary was born Bridget Boland around 1869 in Ballyvadlea, [[County Tipperary]], Ireland.<ref>Her father is recorded as giving her age as 26 years old in 1895.</ref> She married Michael Cleary in August 1887. The couple met in [[Clonmel]] in August 1887, where he worked as a [[Cooper (profession)|cooper]] and she served as a dressmaker's apprentice.<ref name=\"google1\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Nq4rAQAAMAAJ&q=bridget+cleary&dq=bridget+cleary&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjgkf630PXKAhVKExoKHZEaCOgQ6AEIHDAA|title=The Burning of Bridget Cleary: A True Story|author=Angela Bourke|website=Books.google.co.uk|accessdate=24 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter the marriage, she returned to her [[townland]] of Ballyvadlea to live with her parents, while Michael continued to work as a cooper in Clonmel. During this period of living apart, Bridget's independence grew, with her keeping her own flock of chickens and selling the eggs to neighbours. Somewhat unusually for the era and location, she was also a professional woman. She obtained a [[Singer sewing machine]], state of the art at the time, and was variously described as a dressmaker and a [[Hatmaking|milliner]]. Despite their eight years of marriage, the couple had had no children by the time of Bridget's death. Following the death of Bridget's mother, the Clearys found themselves responsible for Bridget's elderly father, Patrick Boland. His residence with the couple enabled them to secure a house reserved for labourers. Neither Bridget nor Michael was entitled to this cottage, but as Patrick had been a labourer in his youth, they were able to acquire the best house in the village. However, there was no widespread interest in the house, as it was built on the site of a supposed [[Fairy fort|fairy ringfort]].<ref name=\"google1\"/>\n\n==\"Disappearance\"==\nBridget was reported missing in March 1895. She had evidently been ill for several days; her diagnosis was said to be bronchitis. More than a week into her illness, on 13 March 1895, a physician visited her at her home; her condition was considered sufficiently grave that a priest soon followed, to administer [[last rites]]. Several of her friends and family members attended her over the next two days, and a number of home remedies were administered, including one ritual that anticipated her later demise: her father and her husband accused her of being a fairy sent to take Bridget's place. Urine was thrown on her, and she was carried before the fireplace to cast the fairy out.\n\nBy 16 March, rumours were beginning to circulate that Bridget was missing, and the local police began searching for her. Michael was quoted as claiming that his wife had been taken by fairies, and he appeared to be holding a vigil. Witness statements were gathered over the ensuing week, and by the time Bridget Cleary's burnt corpse was found in a shallow grave on 22 March, nine people had been charged in her disappearance, including her husband. A coroner's inquest the next day returned a verdict of death by burning.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\n==Trial==\nLegal hearings ran from 1 April to 6 April 1895. A tenth person had been charged, and one of the original nine was discharged at this stage, leaving nine defendants bound over for trial. The court session began on 3 July, and the [[grand jury]] indicted five of the defendants for murder: Michael Cleary, Patrick Boland, Mary  Kennedy, James Kennedy, and Patrick Kennedy. All nine were indicted on charges of \"wounding.\"{{Clarify|date=October 2013}} The case proceeded on to trial. The evidence showed that on 15 March, Michael summoned Father Ryan back to the Cleary household. Ryan found Bridget alive but agitated. Michael Cleary told the priest that he had not been giving his wife the medicine prescribed by the doctor, because he had no faith in it. According to Ryan, \"Cleary then said, 'People may have some remedy of their own that might do more good than doctor's medicine,' or something to that effect.\" Bridget was given communion, and Ryan departed. Later that night, neighbours and relatives returned to the Cleary house. An argument ensued, again tinged with fairy mythology. {{Clarify|date=May 2013}}\n\nAt some point, Bridget told Michael that the only person who'd gone off with the fairies had been his mother. Michael attempted to force-feed his wife, throwing her down on the ground before the kitchen fireplace and menacing her with a burning piece of wood. Bridget's [[chemise]] caught fire, and Michael then threw lamp oil (kerosene) on Bridget. The witnesses were unclear as to whether she was already dead by this point. Michael kept the others back from her body as it burned, insisting that she was a changeling and had been for a week previously, and that he would get his wife back from the fairies.<ref name=\"burning231\" />\n\nAs part of the trial, the jury was actually led out to the storage building where Bridget's body was being held for burial, and where it was available for viewing. The jury were given the opportunity to see the condition of the body and the extent of her injuries, as well as to personally verify that the body was indeed Bridget's by looking upon her face. What the jury witnessed in the outbuilding convinced them of the horrible suffering Bridget had endured prior to death.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Burning of Bridget Cleary: A True Story|last=Bourke|first=Angela|publisher=Penguin Group USA|date=1 July 2001|isbn=978-0-14-100202-6|location=|pages=132|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\nCharges against one  co-defendants, William Ahearn, were dropped, and three others, John Dunne, Michael Kennedy, and William Kennedy, were convicted of \"wounding\".<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE4D91E3AF93BA35753C1A9669C8B63 David Willis McCullough, \"The Fairy Defense\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 8 October 2000; accessed 23 March 2007.</ref>  Patrick Kennedy was sentenced to 5 years of penal servitude, Michael Kennedy was sentenced to 6 months of hard labor, James Kennedy was sentenced to 18 months of hard labor, William Kennedy was sentenced to 18 months of hard labor, Mary Kennedy was released owing to her age and frailty, Patrick Boland was sentenced to 6 months of hard labor, John Dunne was sentenced to 3 years of penal servitude, and Michael Cleary was found guilty of [[manslaughter]], and sentenced to 20 years of penal servitude; he spent 15 years in prison. He was released from Maryborough (now [[Portlaoise]]) prison on 28 April 1910 and moved to the English city of Liverpool, from which he emigrated to Canada in July of the same year.<ref name=\"burning231\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Nq4rAQAAMAAJ|title=The Burning of Bridget Cleary: A True Story|first=|date=1 July 2001|publisher=Penguin Group USA|year=|isbn=978-0-14-100202-6|location=|page=125|pages=|quote=|via=|author=Angela Bourke}}</ref> On 14 October 1910, a black bordered letter was sent from the office of the Secretary of State, Home Department, London, to the undersecretary, Dublin Castle<ref name=\"burning231\" /> stating that Michael Cleary had emigrated from [[Liverpool]] to [[Montreal]] on 30 June.\n\n==Public reaction and aftermath==\nBridget Cleary's death has remained famous in popular culture. An Irish nursery rhyme reads,\n<blockquote>Are you a witch, or are you a fairy/Or are you the wife of Michael Cleary?</blockquote>\nShe has been popularly described as \"the last witch burned in Ireland\"<ref name=\"Bourke, p. 232\">Bourke, p. 232.</ref> or as the subject of the last of the witchcraft trials,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.controverscial.com/The%20Fairy%20Witch%20of%20Clonmel.htm|title=The Fairy Witch of Clonmel|last=Knowles|first=George|publisher=Controverscial.com|accessdate=24 February 2016}}</ref> although it has been noted<ref name=\"Bourke, p. 232\"/> that Bridget was never actually described as having consorted with the [[Devil]], which is customary with accused witches. Instead, she was thought to have been replaced by a fairy changeling. Her death and the publicity surrounding the trial were regarded as being politically significant at the time. [[Home Rule#Irish home rule|Irish home rule]] was an active political issue in England; [[William Ewart Gladstone]]'s [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] had come to power on a Home Rule platform, but had relatively recently<ref>March 1894 according to Bourke, although the [[Irish Government Bill 1893|Wikipedia article]] gives September 1893.</ref> lost its latest [[Government of Ireland Bill 1893|Irish Government Bill]] in the [[House of Lords]]. Press coverage of the Cleary case occurred in an atmosphere of debate over the Irish people's ability to govern themselves, and worries were expressed about the credulity and superstition of rural Catholics. The coroner who examined Bridget's corpse claimed that \"amongst [[Hottentot (racial term)|Hottentots]] one would not expect to hear of such an occurrence.\"<ref>Bourke, p. 130.</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' covered the story in April<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1895/04/22/102455570.pdf|title=NOT WITCHES, BUT FAIRIES - A New Explanation of the Strange Tragedy in Tipperary.|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=22 April 1895|accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref> and again in July 1895.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1895/07/06/102516444.pdf|title=A WITCH BURNER SENTENCED. - Michael Cleary Condemned to Imprisonment for Twenty Years.|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=6 July 1895|accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe writer [[E. F. Benson]] took a considerable interest in the case, publishing a scholarly commentary on it, \"The Recent 'Witch-Burning at Clonmel'\", in the influential periodical ''[[Nineteenth Century (periodical)|The Nineteenth Century]]'' in June 1895, before the trial itself began. It accepts the defence argument that those involved with Bridget Cleary's death acted out of a genuine belief that she had been possessed by a spirit, had no intention of murder, and were attempting to restore her to her rightful self.  Benson cites a pattern of similar beliefs in \"savage tribes\", with examples from various societies, and talks of \"the enormous force which such beliefs exercise on untutored minds\". He points out that the door of the Cleary house was left open and no attempts were made to keep the assaults on Bridget secret. \"It is inconceivable that, if they had wished to kill her, they would have left the door open, that they should have allowed their shouts to attract the neighbours, or that ten persons should have been admitted to witness the deed. Terrible and ghastly as the case is, we cannot call it wilful murder.\"<ref name=Benson/> The article ends with the statement: \"... if ... they killed, but not with intent to kill, still less should the extreme penalty be inflicted\".<ref name=\"Benson\">[http://gaslight.mtroyal.ca/clonmel.htm Benson, E. F. (1895). \"The Recent 'Witch-Burning' at Clonmel'. ''The Nineteenth Century'' Vol. 37 (1895-Jun), pp 1053\u201358]; accessed 16 September 2010.</ref>\n\nThe [[cultural anthropology|anthropologist]] and [[folklore studies|folklorist]] [[James George Frazer]], himself from a culturally Celtic background, took an interest in the Cleary case and discussed it in the third edition of his magnum opus, ''[[The Golden Bough]]''.<ref>{{Cite book | last = Josephson-Storm | first = Jason | title = The Myth of Disenchantment: Magic, Modernity, and the Birth of the Human Sciences | publisher = University of Chicago Press |location = Chicago| page = 125-7| date = 2017 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=xZ5yDgAAQBAJ | isbn = 0-226-40336-X }}</ref>\n\n==Psychiatric aspects of the case==\nH. O\u2019Connell and P. G. Doyle (2006) speculated that the murder may have been the result of Michael Cleary developing a [[brief psychotic disorder]], which manifested as [[Capgras syndrome]], due to the stress of managing Bridget's illness. This became a case of ''[[folie \u00e0 plusieurs]]'' after he persuaded others that she had been replaced by a fairy. The possibility that others complicit in the murder suffered from [[learning disabilities]] that allowed them to become convinced of the delusion's veracity was also raised.<ref>O\u2019Connell, H., & Doyle, P. G. (2006). The burning of Bridget Cleary: Psychiatric aspects of a tragic tale. Irish Journal of Medical Science, 175(3), 76-78. doi:10.1007/bf03169179</ref>\n\nIt is entirely possible that Micheal Cleary used the changeling explanation to hide his own rising inadequacies as a man and provider. It is evident that Bridget was a very successful businesswoman, a rare thing in rural communities of this era. His demasculation as a result of this may have to contributed to his ease at coming to believe his wife had been replaced.\n\n==In popular culture==\nAn Irish nursery rhyme reads, \"Are you a witch, or are you a fairy/Or are you the wife of Michael Cleary?\"\n\n''The Burning of Bridget Cleary'' by Angela Bourke and ''The Cooper's Wife is Missing'' by Joan Hoff & Marian Yeates, both released independently of each other in 2000, are historical accounts of the case that attempt to contextualize the murder with the belief in fairies in Ireland during the period.\n\nIn 2010, ''The Fairy Wife'', a play by Lawrence Bullock, based on the life of Bridget Cleary, premiered in New York City, at the Producers' Club Theatre, under the auspices of Le Wilhelm and Love Creek Productions.{{Citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n\nEpisode 85 of [[The Irish History Podcast]], broadcast July 11, 2016, gives a detailed account of Bridget Cleary's murder, entitled \"Bridget Cleary - the last woman burned alive in Ireland.\"\n\nThe 2016 song \"Changeling\" by The Riptide Movement is based on the story of Bridget's death.\n\nThe critically acclaimed podcast ''[[Lore (podcast)|Lore]]'' devoted one of its episodes (entitled \"Black Stockings\", broadcast October 13, 2017) to the story of Bridget Cleary's murder. The podcast has since spawned a TV adaption produced and aired by [[Amazon Video]]. The \"Black Stockings\" story was one of the six podcast episodes chosen to be adapted for the TV series. The role of Bridget Cleary was portrayed by [[Holland Roden]], while the role of her husband Michael was portrayed by [[Cathal Pendred]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2017/05/lore-holland-roden-lead-amazon-horror-anthology-series-1202105247/ |title=''Lore'': Holland Roden set as lead in Amazon horror anthology series |author=Denise Petski |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=31 May 2017 |accessdate=15 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{IMDb episode|6967582|Black Stockings}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, ''Porcelain'', a play by Margaret Perry, uses the real-life tragedy of Bridget Cleary as a harrowing backdrop to a modern-day thriller. ''Porcelain'' weaves past and present, myth and fact to explore the parallel stories of two Irish women. It opens in Dublin's [[Abbey Theatre]].<ref>{{ |url=https://www.abbeytheatre.ie/whats-on/porcelain/ |title=''Porcelain'' |date=6 January 2018  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Irish singer-songwriter [[Maija Sofia]] released the song, 'The Wife of Michael Cleary', about the tragic story.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Capgras delusion]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Bourke, Angela. ''The Burning of Bridget Cleary''. New York: Penguin, 2001. {{ISBN|0141002026}}\n* Hoff, Joan and Yeates, Marian. ''The Cooper's Wife Is Missing: The Trials of Bridget Cleary.'' New York: Basic Books, 2000 (original), 2006 (paperback reprint). {{ISBN|978-0465030880}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Bridget Cleary |birth=1870 |death=1895}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cleary, Bridget}}\n[[Category:1860s births]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:Date of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:1895 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish women]]\n[[Category:Murder in 1895]]\n[[Category:Female murder victims]]\n[[Category:Irish murder victims]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Ireland]]\n[[Category:People from Clonmel]]\n[[Category:Uxoricides]]\n[[Category:1890s murders in Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irishwoman killed by her husband, fearing her a changeling}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name = Bridget Cleary\n| image = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = Bridget Boland\n| birth_date = {{birth year|1869}}\n| birth_place = Ballyvadlea, [[County Tipperary]], Ireland\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1895|03|15|1869}}\n| death_place = Ballyvadlea, [[County Tipperary]], Ireland\n| occupation = Dressmaker\n| spouse = Michael Cleary (m. 1887-1895, her death)\n}}\n\n'''Bridget Cleary''' (n\u00e9e '''Boland'''; {{lang-ga|Br\u00edd U\u00ed Chl\u00e9irigh}}; c. 1869 \u2013 15 March 1895) was an Irish woman killed by her husband in 1895. Her death is notable for several peculiarities: the stated motive for the crime was her husband's belief that she had been abducted by [[fairy|fairies]] with a [[changeling]] left in her place; he claimed to have slain only the changeling. The gruesome nature of the case \u2014 she was either [[Death by burning|immolated]] while still alive or set on fire immediately following her death \u2014 prompted extensive press coverage. The trial was closely followed by newspapers in both Ireland and [[Great Britain|Britain]].<ref name=\"McCullough-NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE4D91E3AF93BA35753C1A9669C8B63|author=David Willis McCullough|title=The Fairy Defense|work=New York Times|date=8 October 2000|accessdate=23 March 2007}}</ref> As one reviewer commented, nobody, with the possible exception of the presiding judge, thought it was an ordinary murder case.<ref name=\"McCullough-NYT\"/>\n\n==Early life and marriage==\nCleary was born Bridget Boland around 1869 in Ballyvadlea, [[County Tipperary]], Ireland.<ref>Her father is recorded as giving her age as 26 years old in 1895.</ref> She married Michael Cleary in August 1887. The couple met in [[Clonmel]] in August 1887, where he worked as a [[Cooper (profession)|cooper]] and she served as a dressmaker's apprentice.<ref name=\"google1\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Nq4rAQAAMAAJ&q=bridget+cleary&dq=bridget+cleary&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjgkf630PXKAhVKExoKHZEaCOgQ6AEIHDAA|title=The Burning of Bridget Cleary: A True Story|author=Angela Bourke|website=Books.google.co.uk|accessdate=24 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter the marriage, she returned to her [[townland]] of Ballyvadlea to live with her parents, while Michael continued to work as a cooper in Clonmel. During this period of living apart, Bridget's independence grew, with her keeping her own flock of chickens and selling the eggs to neighbours. Somewhat unusually for the era and location, she was also a professional woman. She obtained a [[Singer sewing machine]], state of the art at the time, and was variously described as a dressmaker and a [[Hatmaking|milliner]]. Despite their eight years of marriage, the couple had had no children by the time of Bridget's death. Following the death of Bridget's mother, the Clearys found themselves responsible for Bridget's elderly father, Patrick Boland. His residence with the couple enabled them to secure a house reserved for labourers. Neither Bridget nor Michael was entitled to this cottage, but as Patrick had been a labourer in his youth, they were able to acquire the best house in the village. However, there was no widespread interest in the house, as it was built on the site of a supposed [[Fairy fort|fairy ringfort]].<ref name=\"google1\"/>\n\n==\"Disappearance\"==\nBridget was reported missing in March 1895. She had evidently been ill for several days; her diagnosis was said to be bronchitis. More than a week into her illness, on 13 March 1895, a physician visited her at her home; her condition was considered sufficiently grave that a priest soon followed, to administer [[last rites]]. Several of her friends and family members attended her over the next two days, and a number of home remedies were administered, including one ritual that anticipated her later demise: her father and her husband accused her of being a fairy sent to take Bridget's place. Urine was thrown on her, and she was carried before the fireplace to cast the fairy out.\n\nBy 16 March, rumours were beginning to circulate that Bridget was missing, and the local police began searching for her. Michael was quoted as claiming that his wife had been taken by fairies, and he appeared to be holding a vigil. Witness statements were gathered over the ensuing week, and by the time Bridget Cleary's burnt corpse was found in a shallow grave on 22 March, nine people had been charged in her disappearance, including her husband. A coroner's inquest the next day returned a verdict of death by burning.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\n==Trial==\nLegal hearings ran from 1 April to 6 April 1895. A tenth person had been charged, and one of the original nine was discharged at this stage, leaving nine defendants bound over for trial. The court session began on 3 July, and the [[grand jury]] indicted five of the defendants for murder: Michael Cleary, Patrick Boland, Mary  Kennedy, James Kennedy, and Patrick Kennedy. All nine were indicted on charges of \"wounding.\"{{Clarify|date=October 2013}} The case proceeded on to trial. The evidence showed that on 15 March, Michael summoned Father Ryan back to the Cleary household. Ryan found Bridget alive but agitated. Michael Cleary told the priest that he had not been giving his wife the medicine prescribed by the doctor, because he had no faith in it. According to Ryan, \"Cleary then said, 'People may have some remedy of their own that might do more good than doctor's medicine,' or something to that effect.\" Bridget was given communion, and Ryan departed. Later that night, neighbours and relatives returned to the Cleary house. An argument ensued, again tinged with fairy mythology. {{Clarify|date=May 2013}}\n\nAt some point, Bridget told Michael that the only person who'd gone off with the fairies had been his mother. Michael attempted to force-feed his wife, throwing her down on the ground before the kitchen fireplace and menacing her with a burning piece of wood. Bridget's [[chemise]] caught fire, and Michael then threw lamp oil (kerosene) on Bridget. The witnesses were unclear as to whether she was already dead by this point. Michael kept the others back from her body as it burned, insisting that she was a changeling and had been for a week previously, and that he would get his wife back from the fairies.<ref name=\"burning231\" />\n\nAs part of the trial, the jury was actually led out to the storage building where Bridget's body was being held for burial, and where it was available for viewing. The jury were given the opportunity to see the condition of the body and the extent of her injuries, as well as to personally verify that the body was indeed Bridget's by looking upon her face. What the jury witnessed in the outbuilding convinced them of the horrible suffering Bridget had endured prior to death.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Burning of Bridget Cleary: A True Story|last=Bourke|first=Angela|publisher=Penguin Group USA|date=1 July 2001|isbn=978-0-14-100202-6|location=|pages=132|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\nCharges against one  co-defendants, William Ahearn, were dropped, and three others, John Dunne, Michael Kennedy, and William Kennedy, were convicted of \"wounding\".<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE4D91E3AF93BA35753C1A9669C8B63 David Willis McCullough, \"The Fairy Defense\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 8 October 2000; accessed 23 March 2007.</ref>  Patrick Kennedy was sentenced to 5 years of penal servitude, Michael Kennedy was sentenced to 6 months of hard labor, James Kennedy was sentenced to 18 months of hard labor, William Kennedy was sentenced to 18 months of hard labor, Mary Kennedy was released owing to her age and frailty, Patrick Boland was sentenced to 6 months of hard labor, John Dunne was sentenced to 3 years of penal servitude, and Michael Cleary was found guilty of [[manslaughter]], and sentenced to 20 years of penal servitude; he spent 15 years in prison. He was released from Maryborough (now [[Portlaoise]]) prison on 28 April 1910 and moved to the English city of Liverpool, from which he emigrated to Canada in July of the same year.<ref name=\"burning231\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Nq4rAQAAMAAJ|title=The Burning of Bridget Cleary: A True Story|first=|date=1 July 2001|publisher=Penguin Group USA|year=|isbn=978-0-14-100202-6|location=|page=125|pages=|quote=|via=|author=Angela Bourke}}</ref> On 14 October 1910, a black bordered letter was sent from the office of the Secretary of State, Home Department, London, to the undersecretary, Dublin Castle<ref name=\"burning231\" /> stating that Michael Cleary had emigrated from [[Liverpool]] to [[Montreal]] on 30 June.\n\n==Public reaction and aftermath==\nBridget Cleary's death has remained famous in popular culture. An Irish nursery rhyme reads,\n<blockquote>Are you a witch, or are you a fairy/Or are you the wife of Michael Cleary?</blockquote>\nShe has been popularly described as \"the last witch burned in Ireland\"<ref name=\"Bourke, p. 232\">Bourke, p. 232.</ref> or as the subject of the last of the witchcraft trials,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.controverscial.com/The%20Fairy%20Witch%20of%20Clonmel.htm|title=The Fairy Witch of Clonmel|last=Knowles|first=George|publisher=Controverscial.com|accessdate=24 February 2016}}</ref> although it has been noted<ref name=\"Bourke, p. 232\"/> that Bridget was never actually described as having consorted with the [[Devil]], which is customary with accused witches. Instead, she was thought to have been replaced by a fairy changeling. Her death and the publicity surrounding the trial were regarded as being politically significant at the time. [[Home Rule#Irish home rule|Irish home rule]] was an active political issue in England; [[William Ewart Gladstone]]'s [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] had come to power on a Home Rule platform, but had relatively recently<ref>March 1894 according to Bourke, although the [[Irish Government Bill 1893|Wikipedia article]] gives September 1893.</ref> lost its latest [[Government of Ireland Bill 1893|Irish Government Bill]] in the [[House of Lords]]. Press coverage of the Cleary case occurred in an atmosphere of debate over the Irish people's ability to govern themselves, and worries were expressed about the credulity and superstition of rural Catholics. The coroner who examined Bridget's corpse claimed that \"amongst [[Hottentot (racial term)|Hottentots]] one would not expect to hear of such an occurrence.\"<ref>Bourke, p. 130.</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' covered the story in April<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1895/04/22/102455570.pdf|title=NOT WITCHES, BUT FAIRIES - A New Explanation of the Strange Tragedy in Tipperary.|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=22 April 1895|accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref> and again in July 1895.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1895/07/06/102516444.pdf|title=A WITCH BURNER SENTENCED. - Michael Cleary Condemned to Imprisonment for Twenty Years.|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=6 July 1895|accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe writer [[E. F. Benson]] took a considerable interest in the case, publishing a scholarly commentary on it, \"The Recent 'Witch-Burning at Clonmel'\", in the influential periodical ''[[Nineteenth Century (periodical)|The Nineteenth Century]]'' in June 1895, before the trial itself began. It accepts the defence argument that those involved with Bridget Cleary's death acted out of a genuine belief that she had been possessed by a spirit, had no intention of murder, and were attempting to restore her to her rightful self.  Benson cites a pattern of similar beliefs in \"savage tribes\", with examples from various societies, and talks of \"the enormous force which such beliefs exercise on untutored minds\". He points out that the door of the Cleary house was left open and no attempts were made to keep the assaults on Bridget secret. \"It is inconceivable that, if they had wished to kill her, they would have left the door open, that they should have allowed their shouts to attract the neighbours, or that ten persons should have been admitted to witness the deed. Terrible and ghastly as the case is, we cannot call it wilful murder.\"<ref name=Benson/> The article ends with the statement: \"... if ... they killed, but not with intent to kill, still less should the extreme penalty be inflicted\".<ref name=\"Benson\">[http://gaslight.mtroyal.ca/clonmel.htm Benson, E. F. (1895). \"The Recent 'Witch-Burning' at Clonmel'. ''The Nineteenth Century'' Vol. 37 (1895-Jun), pp 1053\u201358]; accessed 16 September 2010.</ref>\n\nThe [[cultural anthropology|anthropologist]] and [[folklore studies|folklorist]] [[James George Frazer]], himself from a culturally Celtic background, took an interest in the Cleary case and discussed it in the third edition of his magnum opus, ''[[The Golden Bough]]''.<ref>{{Cite book | last = Josephson-Storm | first = Jason | title = The Myth of Disenchantment: Magic, Modernity, and the Birth of the Human Sciences | publisher = University of Chicago Press |location = Chicago| page = 125-7| date = 2017 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=xZ5yDgAAQBAJ | isbn = 0-226-40336-X }}</ref>\n\n==Psychiatric aspects of the case==\nH. O\u2019Connell and P. G. Doyle (2006) speculated that the murder may have been the result of Michael Cleary developing a [[brief psychotic disorder]], which manifested as [[Capgras syndrome]], due to the stress of managing Bridget's illness. This became a case of ''[[folie \u00e0 plusieurs]]'' after he persuaded others that she had been replaced by a fairy. The possibility that others complicit in the murder suffered from [[learning disabilities]] that allowed them to become convinced of the delusion's veracity was also raised.<ref>O\u2019Connell, H., & Doyle, P. G. (2006). The burning of Bridget Cleary: Psychiatric aspects of a tragic tale. Irish Journal of Medical Science, 175(3), 76-78. doi:10.1007/bf03169179</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nAn Irish nursery rhyme reads, \"Are you a witch, or are you a fairy/Or are you the wife of Michael Cleary?\"\n\n''The Burning of Bridget Cleary'' by Angela Bourke and ''The Cooper's Wife is Missing'' by Joan Hoff & Marian Yeates, both released independently of each other in 2000, are historical accounts of the case that attempt to contextualize the murder with the belief in fairies in Ireland during the period.\n\nIn 2010, ''The Fairy Wife'', a play by Lawrence Bullock, based on the life of Bridget Cleary, premiered in New York City, at the Producers' Club Theatre, under the auspices of Le Wilhelm and Love Creek Productions.{{Citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n\nEpisode 85 of [[The Irish History Podcast]], broadcast July 11, 2016, gives a detailed account of Bridget Cleary's murder, entitled \"Bridget Cleary - the last woman burned alive in Ireland.\"\n\nThe 2016 song \"Changeling\" by The Riptide Movement is based on the story of Bridget's death.\n\nThe critically acclaimed podcast ''[[Lore (podcast)|Lore]]'' devoted one of its episodes (entitled \"Black Stockings\", broadcast October 13, 2017) to the story of Bridget Cleary's murder. The podcast has since spawned a TV adaption produced and aired by [[Amazon Video]]. The \"Black Stockings\" story was one of the six podcast episodes chosen to be adapted for the TV series. The role of Bridget Cleary was portrayed by [[Holland Roden]], while the role of her husband Michael was portrayed by [[Cathal Pendred]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2017/05/lore-holland-roden-lead-amazon-horror-anthology-series-1202105247/ |title=''Lore'': Holland Roden set as lead in Amazon horror anthology series |author=Denise Petski |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=31 May 2017 |accessdate=15 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{IMDb episode|6967582|Black Stockings}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, ''Porcelain'', a play by Margaret Perry, uses the real-life tragedy of Bridget Cleary as a harrowing backdrop to a modern-day thriller. ''Porcelain'' weaves past and present, myth and fact to explore the parallel stories of two Irish women. It opens in Dublin's [[Abbey Theatre]].<ref>{{ |url=https://www.abbeytheatre.ie/whats-on/porcelain/ |title=''Porcelain'' |date=6 January 2018  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Irish singer-songwriter [[Maija Sofia]] released the song, 'The Wife of Michael Cleary', about the tragic story.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Capgras delusion]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Bourke, Angela. ''The Burning of Bridget Cleary''. New York: Penguin, 2001. {{ISBN|0141002026}}\n* Hoff, Joan and Yeates, Marian. ''The Cooper's Wife Is Missing: The Trials of Bridget Cleary.'' New York: Basic Books, 2000 (original), 2006 (paperback reprint). {{ISBN|978-0465030880}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Bridget Cleary |birth=1870 |death=1895}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cleary, Bridget}}\n[[Category:1860s births]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:Date of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:1895 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish women]]\n[[Category:Murder in 1895]]\n[[Category:Female murder victims]]\n[[Category:Irish murder victims]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Ireland]]\n[[Category:People from Clonmel]]\n[[Category:Uxoricides]]\n[[Category:1890s murders in Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Beckaweina", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePsychiatric aspects of the case:Added theory based in my own training and knowledge.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridget_Cleary"}
{"title_page": "Cardiff City Line", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name                            = Cardiff City Line\n| image                           = Class142 Danescourt Up3.jpg\n| caption                         = A [[British Rail Class 142|Class 142]] train approaches {{rws|Danescourt}}<br>''en route'' to {{rws|Coryton|Cardiff|Coryton}}\n| type                            = Heavy Rail\n| system                          = [[National Rail]]\n| locale                          = [[Cardiff]]\n| start                           = {{rws|Cardiff Central}}\n| end                             = {{rws|Radyr}}\n| stations                        = 4\n| open                            = 1987\n| owner                           = [[Network Rail]]\n| operator                        = [[Transport for Wales Rail|Transport for Wales]]\n| character                       =\n| stock                           = [[diesel multiple unit]]s of<br>[[Pacer (train)|Pacer]] classes [[British Rail Class 142|142]] and [[British Rail Class 143|143]] and<br>[[Sprinter (train)|Sprinter]] classes [[British Rail Class 150|150]] and [[British Rail Class 153|153]]\n| linelength                      = {{convert|4|mi|66|chain|km|lk=in}}<ref>{{cite book |last1=Yonge |first1=John |last2=Padgett |first2=David |editor-last=Bridge |editor-first=Mike |title=Railway Track Diagrams 3: Western |edition=5th |date=August 2010 |origyear=1989 |publisher=Trackmaps |location=Bradford on Avon |isbn=978-0-9549866-6-7 |at=maps 22 & 28B |ref=harv }}</ref>\n| tracks                          = [[double track]] throughout\n| gauge                           = {{track gauge|uksg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge                       =\n| speed                           =\n| map                             = {{Cardiff City Line|inline=1}}\n}}\nThe '''City Line''' is a [[Commuter rail in the United Kingdom|commuter]] [[railway line]] in [[Cardiff]] that runs between {{rws|Radyr}} and {{rws|Cardiff Central}} via {{rws|Fairwater}}.\n\n==History==\nThe line was opened by the [[Taff Vale Railway]] in 1859, as part of its route from {{stnlnk|Radyr}} to the [[Penarth Dock|docks]] at [[Penarth]].<ref>[http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Penarth_Harbour,_Dock_and_Railway Grace's Guide \u2013 Penarth Dock & Harbour Railway] www.gracesguide.co.uk; Retrieved 12 September 2013</ref>  Subsequent construction by the TVR added links to {{rws|Cardiff Central}} and to the {{rws|Penarth}} Extension Railway by 1878. Originally the line was freight-only, but over the years saw regular use for empty passenger trains thanks to its links with the depot at [[Cardiff Canton TMD]]  and also for football specials to [[Ninian Park]] stadium and periodic engineering diversions.<ref>[http://www.walesrails.co.uk/c.html Wales Rail \u2013 Cardiff City Line] www.walesrail.co.uk; Retrieved 12 September 2013</ref>\n\nThe first regular passenger service was introduced to the line on 5 October 1987, when three new stations were opened at {{rws|Waun-gron Park}}, {{rws|Fairwater}} and {{rws|Danescourt}}, and regular service was introduced to the previously existing {{rws|Ninian Park}} station. The new service was introduced by [[British Rail]] in co-operation with  the [[Mid Glamorgan]] and [[South Glamorgan]] County Councils.<ref name=\"Walters\">{{cite book |last1=Walters |first1=Laurence |title=Railways of Cardiff |date=1995 |publisher=Ian Allan Ltd|isbn=0-7110-2380-8 |page=80}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\n\nThere are currently trains every half hour which drop to every hour in the evenings on Mondays-Saturdays. There is no Sunday service on the line.\n\nThe line serves these stations:\n* {{rws|Radyr}}\n* {{rws|Danescourt}}\n* {{rws|Fairwater}}\n* {{rws|Waun-Gron Park}}\n* {{rws|Ninian Park}}\n* {{rws|Cardiff Central}}\n* {{rws|Cardiff Queen Street}}\n\nServices normally continue to {{rws|Coryton|Cardiff}} via the [[Coryton Line]].\n\n[[Transport for Wales Rail|Transport for Wales]] currently operates the line as part of the former [[Valley Lines]] network. TfW succeeded the previous franchisee [[Arriva Trains Wales]] in October 2018. Some freight services also use the line.\n\nThe line is also used as a diversionary route for trains serving {{rws|Merthyr Tydfil}}, {{rws|Aberdare}} and {{rws|Treherbert}} when the line between {{rws|Cardiff Queen Street}} and Radyr is closed for engineering work. In the past there were shuttle trains on the line to serve {{rws|Pontypridd}} and beyond with one stop at {{rws|Ninian Park}}.\n\n==Trains==\nATW operates the line with [[diesel multiple unit]]s of [[Pacer (train)|Pacer]] classes [[British Rail Class 142|142]] and [[British Rail Class 143|143]] and [[Sprinter (train)|Sprinter]] classes [[British Rail Class 150|150]] and [[British Rail Class 153|153]]. The Pacers do not comply with the [[Disability Discrimination Act 1995]] and so will have to be withdrawn by 2019.\n\n==Electrification==\nOn 16 July 2012 plans the [[Department for Transport]] announced plans to electrify the line. This will require new [[electric multiple unit]] trains and should reduce journey times, operating costs and maintenance costs. The DfT intends the work to start between 2014 and 2019.<ref name=BBC-2012-07-16>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-18852955 |title=Rail electrification to Swansea and south Wales valleys welcomed |publisher=BBC Online |date=16 July 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nThe announcement was made as an extension of the electrification of the [[South Wales Main Line]] from {{rws|Cardiff Central}} to {{rws|Swansea}} and the electrification of the south Wales [[Valleys & Cardiff Local Routes|Valley Lines]] at a total cost of \u00a3350 million.<ref name=BBC-2012-07-16/> This in turn is part of a \u00a39.4 billion investment in railways in England and Wales.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18851907 |title=\u00a39bn railway investment announced by coalition |publisher=BBC Online |date=16 July 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of railway stations in Cardiff]]\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Railway lines in Wales}}\n{{Transport in Cardiff}}\n{{South Wales Metro}}\n\n[[Category:Railway lines in Wales]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Cardiff|City Line]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1987]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name                            = Cardiff City Line\n| image                           = Class142 Danescourt Up3.jpg\n| caption                         = A [[British Rail Class 142|Class 142]] train approaches {{rws|Danescourt}}<br>''en route'' to {{rws|Coryton|Cardiff|Coryton}}\n| type                            = Heavy Rail\n| system                          = [[National Rail]]\n| locale                          = [[Cardiff]]\n| start                           = {{rws|Cardiff Central}}\n| end                             = {{rws|Radyr}}\n| stations                        = 4\n| open                            = 1987\n| owner                           = [[Network Rail]]\n| operator                        = [[Transport for Wales Rail|Transport for Wales]]\n| character                       = \n| stock                           = [[diesel multiple unit]]s of<br>[[Pacer (train)|Pacer]] classes [[British Rail Class 142|142]] and [[British Rail Class 143|143]] and<br>[[Sprinter (train)|Sprinter]] classes [[British Rail Class 150|150]] and [[British Rail Class 153|153]]\n| linelength                      = {{convert|4|mi|66|chain|km|lk=in}}<ref>{{cite book |last1=Yonge |first1=John |last2=Padgett |first2=David |editor-last=Bridge |editor-first=Mike |title=Railway Track Diagrams 3: Western |edition=5th |date=August 2010 |origyear=1989 |publisher=Trackmaps |location=Bradford on Avon |isbn=978-0-9549866-6-7 |at=maps 22 & 28B |ref=harv }}</ref>\n| tracks                          = [[double track]] throughout\n| gauge                           = {{track gauge|uksg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge                       = \n| speed                           = \n| map                             = {{Cardiff City Line|inline=1}}\n}}\nThe '''City Line''' is a [[Commuter rail in the United Kingdom|commuter]] [[railway line]] in [[Cardiff]] that runs between {{rws|Radyr}} and {{rws|Cardiff Central}} via {{rws|Fairwater}}.\n\n==History==\nThe line was opened by the [[Taff Vale Railway]] in 1859, as part of its route from {{stnlnk|Radyr}} to the [[Penarth Dock|docks]] at [[Penarth]].<ref>[http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Penarth_Harbour,_Dock_and_Railway Grace's Guide \u2013 Penarth Dock & Harbour Railway] www.gracesguide.co.uk; Retrieved 12 September 2013</ref>  Subsequent construction by the TVR added links to {{rws|Cardiff Central}} and to the {{rws|Penarth}} Extension Railway by 1878. Originally the line was freight-only, but over the years saw regular use for empty passenger trains thanks to its links with the depot at [[Cardiff Canton TMD]]  and also for football specials to [[Ninian Park]] stadium and periodic engineering diversions.<ref>[http://www.walesrails.co.uk/c.html Wales Rail \u2013 Cardiff City Line] www.walesrail.co.uk; Retrieved 12 September 2013</ref> \n\nThe first regular passenger service was introduced to the line on 5 October 1987, when three new stations were opened at {{rws|Waun-gron Park}}, {{rws|Fairwater}} and {{rws|Danescourt}}, and regular service was introduced to the previously existing {{rws|Ninian Park}} station. The new service was introduced by [[British Rail]] in co-operation with  the [[Mid Glamorgan]] and [[South Glamorgan]] County Councils.<ref name=\"Walters\">{{cite book |last1=Walters |first1=Laurence |title=Railways of Cardiff |date=1995 |publisher=Ian Allan Ltd|isbn=0-7110-2380-8 |page=80}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\n\nThere are currently trains every half hour which drop to every hour in the evenings on Mondays-Saturdays. There is no Sunday service on the line.\n\nThe line serves these stations:\n*{{rws|Radyr}}\n*{{rws|Danescourt}}\n*{{rws|Fairwater}}\n*{{rws|Waun-Gron Park}}\n*{{rws|Ninian Park}}\n*{{rws|Cardiff Central}}\n*{{rws|Cardiff Queen Street}}\n\nServices normally continue to {{rws|Coryton|Cardiff}} via the [[Coryton Line]].\n\n[[Transport for Wales Rail|Transport for Wales]] currently operates the line as part of the former [[Valley Lines]] network. TfW succeeded the previous franchisee [[Arriva Trains Wales]] in October 2018. Some freight services also use the line.\n\nThe line is also used as a diversionary route for trains serving {{rws|Merthyr Tydfil}}, {{rws|Aberdare}} and {{rws|Treherbert}} when the line between {{rws|Cardiff Queen Street}} and Radyr is closed for engineering work. In the past there were shuttle trains on the line to serve {{rws|Pontypridd}} and beyond with one stop at {{rws|Ninian Park}}.\n\n==Trains==\nATW operates the line with [[diesel multiple unit]]s of [[Pacer (train)|Pacer]] classes [[British Rail Class 142|142]] and [[British Rail Class 143|143]] and [[Sprinter (train)|Sprinter]] classes [[British Rail Class 150|150]] and [[British Rail Class 153|153]]. The Pacers do not comply with the [[Disability Discrimination Act 1995]] and so will have to be withdrawn by 2019.\n\n==Electrification==\nOn 16 July 2012 plans the [[Department for Transport]] announced plans to electrify the line. This will require new [[electric multiple unit]] trains and should reduce journey times, operating costs and maintenance costs. The DfT intends the work to start between 2014 and 2019.<ref name=BBC-2012-07-16>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-18852955 |title=Rail electrification to Swansea and south Wales valleys welcomed |publisher=BBC Online |date=16 July 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nThe announcement was made as an extension of the electrification of the [[South Wales Main Line]] from {{rws|Cardiff Central}} to {{rws|Swansea}} and the electrification of the south Wales [[Valleys & Cardiff Local Routes|Valley Lines]] at a total cost of \u00a3350 million.<ref name=BBC-2012-07-16/> This in turn is part of a \u00a39.4 billion investment in railways in England and Wales.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-18851907 |title=\u00a39bn railway investment announced by coalition |publisher=BBC Online |date=16 July 2012 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of railway stations in Cardiff]]\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Railway lines in Wales}}\n{{Transport in Cardiff}}\n{{South Wales Metro}}\n\n[[Category:Railway lines in Wales]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Cardiff|City Line]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1987]]\n", "name_user": "Davey2010", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardiff_City_Line"}
